<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Turnout in German General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- German election officials said
that they have registered a record turnout so far in the general
elections on Sunday which were described by pollsters as the
closest one in the country's post-war era.
</P>
<P>
By 2. p.m. local time (1200 GMT), about 47 percent of the 60.5
million eligible voters have cast their ballots, the highest level
since the German reunification in 1990, officials said.
</P>
<P>
At stake is whether German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's current
centre-right ruling coalition, consisting of his CDU, its Bavarian
sister party Christian Social Union (CSU) as well as the junior
partner Free Democratic Party (FDP), would remain in power, or
whether the leftist Social Democratic Party (SPD) will take over
in alliance with the Greens after 16 years in opposition.
</P>
<P>
"I'm feeling fine, but I don't want to conceal the fact that
I'm a little bit excited," said Gerhard Schroeder, SPD's
chancellor candidate, at a polling station in Hanover.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, who is fighting for an unprecedented fifth term in
office, also told reporters at his polling station in Ludwighafen
that he had a good mood as the moment of the truth approaching.
</P>
<P>
"We have fought a good campaign. I'm confident we'll win," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Almost all pre-election opinion polls have pointed to a
cliffhanger vote, with Schroeder's SPD only enjoying a marginal
lead over Kohl's conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Polls will be closed at 6 p.m. local time (1600 GMT) with the
first exit polls due to be released by major German television
networks shortly afterward. However, due to Germany's complex
electoral system and the possible neck-to-neck race, the first
preliminary official results could only be expected around
midnight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
