<HEADLINE> Israeli Arabs Clash with Police, 38 Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 27 (Xinhua) -- violent clashes broke out
between Israeli Arabs and Israeli police Sunday over a land
dispute in north-central Israel, injuring 38, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The clashes took place near the Arab town of Umm Al-Fahem,
30 kilometers southeast of the port city of Haifa, when police
moved in to tear down a tent erected by Arab protesters three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The protesters claimed the land was unfairly confiscated by
the Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
The Arab protesters threw rocks and firebombs at the
police, who responded with tear gas.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-nine Arabs, including mayor of Umm Al-Fahem, and nine
policemen were injured.
</P>
<P>
A protester told the radio that police also fired
rubber-coated bullets and live ammunition.
</P>
<P>
Israeli authorities have said that the disputed area, near the
northern edge of the West Bank, is within an Israeli army firing
range.
</P>
<P>
They also said that an agreement had been reached with the
residents there to nationalize about 50 hectares of land in
exchange for about six times as much land elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said they sent police to evict the protesters
after they failed to negotiate a leave on their own.
</P>
<P>
About 20 percent of Israel's 5.9 million population are Arabs,
living within the original boundaries of the state. Enitem



27/09/98 16:18 GMT

NNNN
00:15 00:15 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
