<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Urgent) Germany's SPD Scores Clearly Lead Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) came clearly ahead of incumbent Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's conservative Union parties in the general elections
Sunday and appeared to have enough votes to form the next German
government in alliance with the Greens, the first exit polls
predicted.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary projections broadcast by the German ZDF
television network immediately after the close of the polls put
the SPD at 41 percent, six percentage points ahead of Kohl's
Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and its Bavarian sister party,
the Christian Social Union (CSU), which came at only 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
The projections put the SPD's possible allies, the Greens, and
Kohl's junior partner, the Free Democratic Party (FDP), both at
6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS), which grew out of the
East German communist party, received 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The projections point to the end of the Kohl era. Kohl has been
German chancellor since 1982.
</P>
<P>
Due to Germany's complex electoral system, the first official
preliminary results were expected at around midnight (2200 GMT).
</P>
</TEXT>
