<HEADLINE> Israel Warns Iran not to Threaten with Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai has warned Iran not to threaten Israel with its
Shihab (Meteor)-3 ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai made the warning at a meeting of Knesset (Parliament)
Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai noted that Israel has been monitoring the Shihab
project for some time and Israel has the capability to defend its
territory and residents, and to deter Iran from doing anything
against the Jewish country.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai stressed that the anti-missile Arrow defense system,
which is developing under the support of the U.S., together with
other defense approaches will provide the country with a solution
in the long run.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai's words came after Iran formally unveiled its
Shihab-3 missiles during a military parade on Friday. The newly
developed weapon has a range of 1,300 kilometers, which means it
is capable of reaching Israel and the U.S. military bases in Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Defense Minister Ali Shamkhani said Saturday that Iran
will develop a new missile that will outdistance medium-range
Shihab-3.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Knesset member Ephrain Sneh told the meeting that
it is not a matter of if but when Iran will develop a nuclear
missile capable of hitting Israel.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Israel must consider planning a preemptive strike
against Iran.
</P>
<P>
But Mordechai criticized Sneh's talk about the preemptive
strike as "damaging and unnecessary." 
</P>
</TEXT>
