<HEADLINE> Schroeder Wins German Election Against Kohl, TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Gerhard Schroeder, chancellor
candidate of Germany's main opposition Social Democratic Party
(SPD), won the general election Sunday, bringing to the incumbent
German chancellor Helmut Kohl a clear defeat, preliminary
projections issued by German television networks said.
</P>
<P>
According to the projections released by the ARD network,
Schroeder's SPD has won 41.2 percent of the vote against 35.7
percent for Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and its
Bavarian sister party, Christian Social Union (CSU).
</P>
<P>
The German ZDF television network gave the SPD 40.9 percent and
Kohl's CDU/CSU alliance 35.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The SPD's potential coalition partner, the Greens, and Kohl's
current junior partner, the Free Democratic Party (FDP), were both
quoted at around 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS), which grew out of the
East German communist party, is hovering at about 5.0 percent, the
projections showed.
</P>
<P>
The clear lead over Kohl's conservatives brought wild cheers at
the SPD headquarters in Bonn. "We has become the strongest party.
Gerhard Schroeder will be federal chancellor," declared SPD party
manager Franz Muenterfering.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, CDU General Secretary Peter Hintze has
conceded defeat. "It is bitter defeat for us," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
