<HEADLINE> Spencer: Cyprus Will Join EU Regardless of Developments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- President of the European
Parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee Tom Spencer stressed in
Greece Sunday that Cyprus would join the European Union (EU)
regardless of developments in the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the northern Greek city of Thessaloniki while
attending a conference, Spencer said that Cyprus' entry to the EU
would reduce the possibility of any Turkish offensive on the
divided island, according to the semi-official Athens News Agency
(ANA).
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into two rival sectors since the
Turkish invasion and occupation of its northern part in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided last December that Cyprus be included in its
list of countries waiting to join the group. The Cypriot
government led by President Glafcos Clerides welcomed the EU
decision because it believed that this would help speed up the
settlement of the protracted Cyprus problem, but Turkey, which
also wants to be a member of the EU, and the Turkish Cypriots in
northern Cyprus opposed the EU decision.
</P>
<P>
The situation on the island has now been tense with the nearing
of the planned deployment later this year of the Russian-made
S-300 anti-aircraft missiles in Cyprus, which says that such a
move should be seen as a self-defense measure to partially
counterbalance Turkey's military superiority on the island.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which keeps some 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus, has
threatened to use force to prevent the missile installation,
claiming that the missiles would be a threat to the Turkish
Cypriot community and to the Turkish mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
