<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Folk Dances, Symphony Back on Stage in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Folk dances and symphony are
back on the stage in Iran after nearly two decades, as the
government vows to promote the status of tourism in the country.
</P>
<P>
Dressed in local colorful costumes, of course in light of
Islamic dressing codes, six Iranian actresses on Sunday performed
a ground-breaking folk dance for senior Iranian officials and
foreign diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the life of women in mountainous areas in the
northern Gilan province, the actresses walked around on the stage
with tea baskets on their shoulders, picked tea leaves and brought
them back home.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied with traditional folk music played with waist
drums and tambourines, the actresses then joined 12 actors to
show the countryside life on the threshing ground: men are
thrashing rice with sticks while women are winnowing the chaff.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time to perform folk dances in Iran publicly,
particularly by actresses in front of senior officials and foreign
diplomats," an official said after President Mohammad Khatami left
the theater in the Vahdat Hall, downtown Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The 1979 Islamic Revolution has influenced every aspect of life
of the Iranian people, and performances of folk dances and western
symphony have been rare since.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's programs were presented to mark the World Tourism Day
and the beginning of Iranian Tourism Week.
</P>
<P>
Folk dances of Iranian Kurds are the miniature of pastoral life
and the Busheri dances present fishing in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
A grand symphony orchestra also appeared on the stage,
performing Iranian classic music and songs in praise of the
beautiful land of the Iranian nation and their civilization.
</P>
<P>
Iran has the attraction to world tourists due to its rich
culture, varied natural scenes and historical remains, officials
here said.
</P>
<P>
Iran is among the first 10 countries in the world which enjoy
rich historical sites, President Khatami told the audience, but
unfortunately Iran's tourism has not gained an appropriate
position in the world.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the world's revenue from tourism reached 440
billion U.S. dollars, while Iran's tourism only fetched 350
million dollars, head of Iran's Tourism Organization Mohammad
Moezeddin said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism will enhance understanding among different nations,
thus expanding peaceful international relations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said Iran should remove obstacles on the way of
development of tourism in Iran, but he did not name them.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here hope that developing tourism will bring fresh air
to the society and lead to relaxation of some of the strict
rules. To request every woman entering the country to wear scarf,
for one, is daunting away a large portion of tourists, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
