<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Hails Turkey's Decision to Restore Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi embassy in Ankara
Sunday welcomed Turkey's decision to restore full diplomatic
relations with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi embassy sources, who asked not to be named, said that
T. Hamandi, charge d'affaires of the embassy, called Turkey's
decision "a step in the right direction." without saying whether
the Iraqi government would send its own ambassador to Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit announced on
Saturday that his country is ready to send an ambassador soon to
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Hamandi did not say whether Iraq would dispatch an ambassador
back to Turkey. Iraq's ambassador returned home last year for, what
Hamandi said, administrative reasons.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has not had an ambassador in Baghdad since the 1991 Gulf
War, which drove Iraqi troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the two countries soured due to disputes
over Ankara's close ties with the United States, which led the
multi-national forces in the Gulf War, sharing of water resources
and Turkey's repeated military actions in northern Iraq against
Turkey's Kurdish separatists.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the unexpected warm-up of relations
between the two neighbors was prompted by a U.S.-brokered
agreement between two Kurdish groups, which have been fighting for
controlling northern Iraq under a safe heaven set up by western
allies after the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The Kurdistan Democratic Party and the Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan signed a peace accord in Washington last week to pave
the way for an elected Kurdish government in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Both Ankara and Baghdad are worried that the move would
destabilize the region and constitute threats to the security of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey fears that the establishment of a Kurdish administration
in northern Iraq would encourage Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party to intensify the war in its southeast for an
independent Kurdish state, which it has been fighting for since
1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
