<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills 200 in Central Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Two hundred people
died of cholera in central region of Tanzania during the first
eight months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Health officials of the Morogoro Region in central Tanzania
have blamed street vendors for selling unclean food, which has
made more than 9,000 people contract cholera.
</P>
<P>
The Regional Health Officer Nicolas Masaoe said at a seminar
for street vendors in Morogoro Friday that most of the cases
occurred after people ate food prepared or preserved in
non-hygienic conditions, according to reports reaching here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At the seminar, the Registrar of the National Food Control
Program, Fabian Magoma, directed local government at various
levels to make the vendors comply with sanitary standards.
</P>
<P>
He said more than 90 percent of urban citizens eat food sold
by vendors and therefore it is important for the authorities to
ensure the safety of food.
</P>
<P>
The program, jointly run by the Ministry of Health and the
World Health Organization (WHO), was launched in 1978 in a bid to
safeguard cleanness of food sold in streets.
</P>
<P>
Cholera is a leading killer in Tanzania. Statistics show that
more than 36,000 people contracted the epidemic disease in the
east African country last year, with a death toll of 2,124.
</P>
</TEXT>
