<HEADLINE> Zadornov: Russian Gov't to Correct Decisions on GKO-OFZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Newly-appointed Russian
Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov said Sunday that the government
is drafting a scheme for converting the August 17 decisions on
State Short-Term Bonds (GKO) and Federal Loan Bonds with Fixed
Income (OFZ).
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency cited Zadornov as reporting that the
steps taken by the government and the Central Bank of Russia on
GKO and OFZ were dictated by the aggravated financial situation in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Zadornov said "a collapse began in several directions:" notably
the banking system lapsed, some banks suspended payments to the
budget, investors started to withdraw money and the reserves of
the CBR became insufficient to maintain the ruble foreign exchange
rate.
</P>
<P>
During the 40 days since August 17, no decisions of principal
importance were worked out, said Zadornov. The situation remains
undetermined, which is the worst thing, while banks continue to
die, economic agents don't work and many people transfer money
abroad, he noted.
</P>
<P>
According to former deputy head of the Presidential
Administration Alexander Livshits, President Boris Yeltsin "was
probably briefed on the August 17 decisions, but he was unlikely
to be briefed on all the possible options in the situation in
mid-August."
</P>
<P>
Those decisions were unavoidable, Livshits said. However, he
said, their organization and technological form was a flight from
the positions instead of a withdrawal arranged to accommodate the
consequences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
