<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia has decided to sell 92,000 shares, or 92
percent of the capital of its airlines, at a price of 120 Tunisian
dinars (110 U.S. dollars) for a share, the Arabic-language
Al-Hayat daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The company founded in 1991 has medium-size aircraft. It
operates flights between the capital Tunis and five other cities,
namely Tobruk, Manstere, Safaqis, Jerba and Touzar, and between
Tunis and Veletta in Malta.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Majlis (Parliament) Sunday approved the
general outlines of a plan to authorize the establishment of a
non-governmental bank.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the private sector can hold up to 49 percent of
the bank's shares, leaving the cooperatives with the controlling
shares of 51 percent of the bank.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The monthly wages of Egyptians working in Lebanon
vary between 400 and 600 U.S. dollars, well above the earnings of
other foreign laborers employed in the country, Egypt's Alam Al
Yom daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A report prepared by the Egyptian labor counselor in Beirut
said the Egyptians in Lebanon have jobs including construction
workers, carpenters, electric technicians, agricultural workers.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Kuwait are expected to sign a number of
agreements in October on encouraging investments and avoiding
double taxation, the Alam Al Yom daily said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will renew the executive protocol for cultural
and technical cooperation and examine the form of a mechanism for
promoting and consolidating bilateral investments.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait so far has invested 2 billion dollars in Egypt, taking
the second place after Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
