<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Profile: Gerhard Schroeder, Winner of Germany's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Gerhard Schroeder, who not long
ago was largely unknown to the outside world, has emerged as the
first German Social Democrat who managed to stop the winning steak
of Germany's veteran chancellor Helmut Kohl during the past 16
years.
</P>
<P>
In Germany's general elections Sunday, he led his Social
Democratic Party (SPD) to a comfortable lead over Kohl's
conservative alliance, a success that will enable him to lead
Europe's most populous nation into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
Born on April 4, 1944 in the small northern German town of
Mossenberg, he never saw his father, who was killed in the same
year while serving in the Nazi army in Romania.
</P>
<P>
As one of five children raised by a war widow who eked out a
living as a cleaning lady, Schroeder's childhood memories include
stealing food to help feed the family and fending off debt
collectors.
</P>
<P>
He studied law and graduated from Goettingen University in
1976. He first became a local parliamentary member of his Lower
Saxony state in 1980 and has been the state premier since 1990.
</P>
<P>
After winning a landslide victory in the state legislature
election at the end of March this year, he finally won his party's
trust and was picked as its chief candidate to challenge Kohl, who
has defeated three SPD contenders since 1982.
</P>
<P>
Describing himself as a pro-business pragmatist, Schroeder says
he understands the challenges faced by German businesses in coping
with the global economy and pledges innovations to improve the
country's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
And based on his miserable childhood experiences, Schroeder
also pledges to restore social justice at a time when Germany's
unemployment is hovering at the near post-war record high of 4
million.
</P>
<P>
Campaigning on a program he called a political "New Center,"
Schroeder's appeal to the large pool of centrist voters has
invited comparisons with U.S. President Bill Clinton and British
Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
But above all, many commentators say that Schroeder has
successfully courted a voters' desire for a political fresh face
after 16 years of Kohl's reign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
