<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100 GMT, September 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Showing another sign of rapprochement with Iran,
Iraq will take part in the International Tehran Fair due to start
on October 1, local daily Baghdad Observer reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This is believed to be the first participation by Iraqis at
such fairs in Iran ever since the start of the 1980-88 war between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted an Iraqi Trade Ministry source as saying
that Iraq's participation in the fair, which will last for 10
days, will provide an opportunity for exchanging points of view
concerning expanding and developing industrial and commercial
cooperation between the two countries. (BC-Iraq-Iran-Tehran Fair)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Tel Aviv District Court sentenced Margalit Har
Shefi to nine months in prison Sunday morning for failing to
prevent the assassination of former Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin.
</P>
<P>
Har Shefi, a close girl friend of convicted assassin Yigal
Amir, also received a suspended sentence of 15 months.
</P>
<P>
The judge said that if Har Shefi had shown more responsibility
and taken a more vigorous action, it would be possible that the
murder might not have occurred. (BC-Israel-Sentence) (repeat with
corrections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Sunday reiterated that the fatwa (religious
decree) issued by late Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini on the life of British writer Salman Rushdie is
irrevocable.
</P>
<P>
"The irrevocability of the late Imam Khomeini's fatwa (on
Rushdie) is a fact," Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud
Mohammadi said to the official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi reiterated Iran's
positions on the insulting book the Satanic Verses and its author
(Rushdie) in his statement on Thursday following his meeting with
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, said Mohammadi.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi ... stressed that any insult to Islamic values would
be under no circumstances acceptable to the Iranians and Muslims
throughout the world. (BC-Iran-Rushdie-Britain)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Jerusalem Magistrate Court on Sunday banned Jewish
settler Avshalom Ladani from entering the Palestinian territories
for his alleged killing of a Palestinian student last week.
</P>
<P>
The Court also ordered the Israeli police to submit on Monday
the investigation report about the incident and then the Court
will decide what legal actions can be taken against Ladani.
</P>
<P>
Ladani, 35 and from Dolev Settlement in the West Bank, opened
fire to a group of Palestinian students on September 17 near the
West Bank city of Ramallah. One Palestinian student was killed
and another injured in the incident. (BC-Israel-Settler)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Iraqi embassy in Ankara Sunday welcomed Turkey's
decision to restore full diplomatic relations with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi embassy sources, who asked not to be named, said that
T. Hamandi, charge d'affaires of the embassy, called Turkey's
decision "a step in the right direction." without saying whether
the Iraqi government would send its own ambassador to Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit announced on
Saturday that his country is ready to send an ambassador soon to
Baghdad. (BC-Turkey-Iraq-Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Sunday condemned the U.S. decision to provide
Israel with more jet-fighters and sophisticated arms, saying that
the move indicated Washington's double-standard policies.
</P>
<P>
Such "irresponsible" support of the U.S. for Israel's military
