<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Minister Visits U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- China's Foreign Minister
Tang Jiaxuan arrived here Sunday in an effort to maintain the
momentum of development in Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at the airport that his three-day visit was
designed to implement the agreements reached by Presidents Jiang
Zemin and Bill Clinton at their summits since last October.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents have agreed to build a constructive
strategic partnership and promote cooperation in varied fields.
High level official exchanges have since been focused on how to
carry out the commitments.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to discuss with U.S. officials the ways of
maintaining the momentum of development in the bilateral
relations," said Tang, who arrived from New York after addressing
the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He was scheduled to meet with his American counterpart,
Madeleine Albright, and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, and
possibly with President Clinton and his National Security Advisor
Sundy Berger.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan issue and trade imbalance might be among the
subjects to be discussed between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton announced during his visit to China in late
June that the United States would not back Taiwan's independence,
its membership in international organizations of sovereign
countries and "Two Chinas" or "One China, One Taiwan" policy.
</P>
<P>
However, the Pentagon recently announced a 350-million U.S.
dollar arms sale to Taiwan, a move which triggered protest from
China. In addition, the House of Representative last week voted to
approve the provision of theater anti-missile systems to the
island.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the Chinese foreign minister would express
China's concerns and urge Washington to adhere to the three joint
communiques signed between the two countries in the 1970s and
1980s. Washington cites the Taiwan Act to justify its arms sales
to the island.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral trade, the U.S. complains about the growing trade
deficit with China and the slow paced negotiations over China's
membership in the World Trade Organization, while China urges the
U.S. to loose control over high-tech exports to China and soften
its terms for China's entry to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
With these problems to be resolved through joint efforts, the
two sides have agreed to cooperate in vital issues like security,
non-proliferation and economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
To materialize the constructive strategic partnership between
China and the United States calls for unremitting efforts from
both sides, Tang told the National Committee on U.S.-China
Relations and the Asia Society in New York Friday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time Tang visits the U.S. since he became
foreign minister early this year. He is expected to leave here for
Canada Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
