<HEADLINE> New Type of Residence Planned for Aging Society (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- More residential housing
providing independent living for the elderly will be built across
China by the year 2010 to meet the needs of an aging society, a
Chinese expert said today.
</P>
<P>
The apartments with bedrooms, living rooms, kitchens and
bathrooms -- will be built for citizens between the age of 60 and
80 in peaceful places in urban and suburban areas, Zhang
Wenfan, chairman of the Chinese Old Citizens Association told a
national conference on elderly housing in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Old people can live a private family life while enjoying daily
services such as maids, laundry and shopping and cooking in such
apartments, Zhang said, adding that health care, entertainment
and educational facilities will also be available.
</P>
<P>
China will become an aged country by the year 2000 with 130
million, over one tenth of the population, over the age of
60. This aged population will continue to grow to 25 percent
of the Chinese population by the year 2050.
</P>
<P>
The old-folks homes and welfare institutes built in the 1950s
for old people without children and parents of martyrs
have already become obsolete with underdeveloped facilities,
according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
He said that many old-folks homes built in the 1980s are
also suffering from a lack of family atmosphere and isolation from
the rest of society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Type of Residence Planned for Aging Society (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 600 residential facilities which can provide independent
living for the elderly have been built across China since the
first was established in Anqing City in east China's Anhui
Province in 1985.
</P>
<P>
"We need not worry about our food and clothing here, and we can
attend all kinds of entertaining activities and talk with friends
who have common interests with us," said Zhang Huizhen, who has
been living with her husband in an apartment for the elderly in
Daqing in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province for two years.
</P>
<P>
The cost of living in such residences is usually moderate and
apt to be covered by pensions and other income often available to
the elderly. They can decide how long they will live in such
places according to their own desires.
</P>
<P>
"I feel more comfortable living here than living with my son,"
said Yu Hongguang, another resident in the Daqing apartment,
"because we have too many differences in life styles."
</P>
<P>
Experts point out that more elderly citizens in China now tend
to live separately from their children, either to reduce conflict
between the generations or to ease the burden on their children.
</P>
<P>
They said the one-child-family policy and longer
life expectancy also intensify the problem of taking care of
the elderly. In some extreme cases, young couples must take
care of the parents of both sides, and grandparents as well.
</P>
<P>
Residential housing which can provide independent living
for the elderly may help resolve the problems, many experts
believe.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
