<HEADLINE> Israeli Right-wingers Threaten to Topple Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli right-wing parties
threatened Monday to topple Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
government if he agrees to withdraw Israeli troops from a further
13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Knesset (Parliament) members of the National Religious Party, a
coalition partner, Hanan Porat and Zvi Handel, have made it clear
that if Netanyahu reaches agreement with the Palestinians on the
pullback, they would rise up against him, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
They said they would side with the opposition in a possible
no-confidence vote to bring down the government, paving the way
for the dissolution of the Knesset and early elections.
</P>
<P>
The Likud-led coalition has a slim majority of 61 members in
the 120-seat Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the hard-line opposition Moledet Party Rahavam Zeevi
said that his party, which has two seats in the Knesset, would
vote for the dissolution of the parliament if the government goes
ahead with the further withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The threats of the right-wingers came as hopes emerged that the
protracted stalemate in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations can
be broken.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat held a three-way meeting late Sunday night with the United
States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in New York.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton also has invited Netanyahu and
Arafat to hold separate talks with him on Monday, which are viewed
to be opportunities to advance the peace process. The latest news
was that the talks may turn out to be a three-way summit to
enhance prospects for settling difference between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly called on Israel to pull back from
another 13 percent of the West Bank in return for Palestinian
crackdown on Islamic militants. The Palestinians have accepted the
proposal, but Israel has not, citing security concerns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
