<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Voters Opt for Change After 16 Years of Kohl Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Germany's veteran chancellor
Helmut Kohl has to swallow a bitter pill on Sunday when he became
the first incumbent chancellor who was voted out of office in the
country's post-war history.
</P>
<P>
Above all explanations, many German commentators agreed that
with 16 successive years in power, Kohl has apparently overstayed
voters' welcome.
</P>
<P>
According to opinion polls, more than two-thirds of Germans
want to see another person at the helm in Bonn. Meanwhile, polls
also showed that there is not much passion behind the demand, no
hatred of Kohl, no anger, just weariness and fatigue, just a
growing yearning for change.
</P>
<P>
At age of 68, Kohl is Germany's longest-serving chancellor and
the most durable Western leader in the post-war era, a statesman
who has secured a place in history as the architect of the German
reunification in 1990 and has been viewed as a leading champion of
European unity.
</P>
<P>
When he announced his intention to run for an unprecedented
fifth term in office in April last year, Kohl said he felt a
personal duty to run again while his country was facing challenges
at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
As a seasoned politician, Kohl is for the first time clearly
having difficulty addressing the mood of the nation, a German
commentator said.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, Schroeder has shrewdly played to the voters'
sentiment by repeatedly underscoring the notion of generational
change during his election race.
</P>
<P>
Campaigning on a concept what he calls the political "New
Center," under which he pledges to combine modernity with social
justice, Schroeder has strong appeals to middle-of-the-road
voters, the ordinary wage-earners, who want some sort of change
but fear too much sacrifice at a time when Germany's unemployment
hovers at near-record high of four million.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Kohl has also seen his popularity slumping in the
eastern half of the country.
</P>
<P>
Once Eastern Germans were so enthusiastic about the
reunification achieved by Kohl, now many blame him for not
creating the "flourishing landscapes" he predicted afterward.
</P>
<P>
Without giving concrete numbers, German pollsters said that
initial examination of the election outcome on Sunday has pointed
to the worst loss for Kohl's party in eastern Germany so far, down
from 39 percent in the 1994 election and 42 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's plunging popularity is in many ways a reflection of the
growing frustration in eastern Germany toward the Western style of
capitalism and a persistently high unemployment rate of about 17
percent, nearly twice that in the west part of the country.
</P>
<P>
As another reflection of the frustration, the Party of
Democratic Socialism, which grew out of the former East Germany's
communist party, broke the five-percent mark for the first time
since 1990 by scoring 5.1 percent of the vote on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Germans comprises about one-fifth of the country's
electorate and were crucial to Kohl's re-election in 1990 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
What change will Schroeder bring to Germany?
</P>
<P>
In his first policy declaration made Sunday evening, Schroeder
pledged to make it his top priority to combat mass
unemployment. He also vowed continuity in foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
During election campaign Schroeder also pledges moderate tax
cuts and more public funding for education and innovations to
improve Germany's competitiveness in a globalized world.
</P>
<P>
But he also vows to reverse some social cutbacks made by Kohl's
government that were designed to shrink the chronic budget deficit
stretched by the German reunification and the country's endeavor
to meet the fiscal conditions for joining the single European
currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
His opponents have accused him of being vague on policy issues.
</P>
<P>
And if Schroeder does hope to pursue his centrist and
pragmatist policies, he still has to persuade his party, which is
still dominated by traditional left-wingers, to come along with
him.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Schroeder also faces tough negotiations with his
potential coalition partner, the ecologist Greens, which has made
a series of radical demands earlier this year, including a call to
triple gasoline prices within ten years and rejection of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization's eastward expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
