<HEADLINE> No Financial Problem for Short-course Swimming Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- There will be neither
financial nor technical problems when Hong Kong hosts the Fourth
International Amateur Swimming Federation (FINA) World
Short-course (25-meter pool) Championships next Spring,
organizers said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The world championships organized by the Hong Kong Amateur
Swimming Association (HKASA) are slated from April 1-4 here.
</P>
<P>
The championships are to be held in four days, with almost
same format as three previous championships. The only exception
is the introduction of semi-finals for the 50-meter and 100-meter
events.
</P>
<P>
The event's organizing committee had so far received entries
of 460 swimmers from 39 countries and regions including the
United States, Australia, Britain and China.
</P>
<P>
And the organizers expect the field to expand to some 1,000
swimmers from 80 to 100 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The organizers had been discussing details with several
sponsors, and the hosts were confident that enough funding will
be available.
</P>
<P>
The feasibility of constructing a portable pool inside the
Hong Kong Coliseum in Kowloon is under full investigation,
organizers said. The pool resembles those at the last world
championships in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no technical difficulties in constructing such a
 pool," said an organizing committee spokesman.
</P>
<P>
During the championships, FINA will hold 13th World Sports
Medicine Congress and FINA General Congress.
</P>
<P>
To further promote the world championships, the HKASA has
decided to hold Hong Kong's first ever open water swimming
competitions, on October 1 at the Repulse Bay Beach.
</P>
<P>
The local association expects to attract some 3,000
participants to four categories -- Junior, Family, Master and
Open. There are two courses -- 625 meters and 500 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
