<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Sue Italy for Discrimination Against Foreign Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
decided to warn Italy of its discriminatory policies against
foreign drivers before threatening to bring the country to court.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union (EU), plans to advise the Italian government that it is
discriminating against drivers from other EU member states when
they violate the country's highway rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
The commission said it would take Italy to the European Court
of Justice if the Italian authorities failed to make a
satisfactory reply within two months.
</P>
<P>
The Italian highway code provides that an offender, whose car
is registered outside Italy, must either pay the police officer a
fine with no chances of appeal or have his/her driving license
confiscated should the driver fail to pay half the maximum penalty
for the offense as a guarantee.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials cited a German driver to support their
argument. The driver, they said, was caught talking over a
cellular phone while driving. He was asked to pay 50,000 lire
(about 27.7 U.S. dollars) to the police officer or 100,000 lire
(55.45 U.S. dollars) as a guarantee for the penalty.
</P>
<P>
When he refused to pay either amount, his driving license was
confiscated.
</P>
<P>
An Italian motorist caught committing the same offense,
however, can either pay 50,000 lire at a police station or by bank
transfer, or appeal within 60 days of receipt of the ticket.
</P>
<P>
The European Court of Justice holds that a European Union
member state may require non-residents to pay a penalty in the way
they opt for in case of infringement rather than paying the fine
immediately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0044 </DOCNO>
