<HEADLINE> WFP Offers Assistance to China's Flood-hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) of
the United Nations will offer emergency assistance of food valued at
87.67 million U.S. dollars to China's flood-ravaged provinces
including Anhui, Hubei and Jiangxi, a WFP official announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
This assistance is the largest ever offered to China by the
WFP, and the largest flood relief assistance China has received
this year.
</P>
<P>
Addressing today's signing ceremony, Chinese Agriculture
Minister Chen Yaobang said, "This project will play a very positive
role in boosting the reconstruction of flood-hit areas and the
restoration of production."
</P>
<P>
The assistance, scheduled to begin in October, will last four
months. The WFP will offer food equivalent to 247,000 tons of rice
to 23 seriously flooded areas, and China will add 480 million yuan
(58 million U.S. dollars) to support the implementation of the
project.
</P>
<P>
The project includes housing construction, farmland restoration
and the reconstruction of rural roads, and will benefit some 5.78
million flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Since 1979, the WFP has offered 60 food assistance projects to
China with a total value of 772 million U.S. dollars. To date,
52 projects have been completed and 8 others are ongoing. Some 24
million people in 191 poverty-stricken counties in China have
benefited from the projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
