<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Di Canio Charged with Misconduct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- England's Football
Association (FA) decided on Monday to charge Paolo Di Canio with
misconduct for his push on referee Paul Alcock.
</P>
<P>
The Sheffield Wednesday striker shoved the official to the
ground during Saturday's match against Arsenal at Hillsborough.
</P>
<P>
Di Canio, who received a red card for the incident, was
initially expected to make an apology but has since accused
Alcock of over-reacting.
</P>
<P>
The Italian now has 14 days to request a personal hearing but,
depending on his response, the FA could bring forward a
disciplinary hearing.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the FA said: "Paolo Di Canio of Sheffield
Wednesday has been charged with misconduct for his reported
assault on referee Paul Alcock."
</P>
<P>
Di Canio, who has been suspended by Sheffield Wednesday and
has flown to Italy with the club's permission, is reported to
have said:
</P>
<P>
"I gave him a shove, but it was hardly done with much force.
</P>
<P>
"He took three or four sideways steps before falling over in
rather a strange way - like someone diving to win a penalty.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Di Canio said that he would wait to see what
punishment was meted out but could be willing to fight it all the
way.
</P>
<P>
"I believe I was the subject of the most intense provocation.
Personally I believe there were several mitigating
circumstances," he told reporters at Heathrow before leaving for
Rome.
</P>
<P>
Di Canio's agent Matteo Roggi said the star was "deeply upset"
over what happened and was prepared to say he is sorry for his
actions.
</P>
<P>
"I feel sure Paolo will decide to issue an apology shortly and
we will then have to see what happens after that. We are also
waiting to hear from Sheffield Wednesday."
</P>
<P>
Premier League referees' officer Philip Don said Alcock "felt
he was pushed very aggressively".
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the BBC's Breakfast News, he said: "The FA could
ban Di Canio for 180 days, given the nature of the offence. That
ban would be effective across the world."
</P>
<P>
The incident at Hillsborough made Alcock, a 45-year-old
shopping center manager, briefly consider quitting as a referee.
</P>
<P>
"I had to think very seriously about what to do with the rest
of my career after what happened," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I was absolutely dumbstruck that something like that could
happen in the Premier League. It's incredible. I couldn't believe
what had taken place, it is totally unacceptable," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines May Reopen on Oct. 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada announced Monday that Philippine Airlines (PAL) may resume
operations on October 7 after its labor leaders finally accepted
an ownership-sharing deal offered by the management.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Estrada said while it will take up to
Wednesday next week to finalize and ratify the agreement being
formalized between the PAL management and its workers, the
operating of PAL "is almost a done deal."
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the PAL Employees Association (PALEA) wrote him
that it was accepting the management's package of benefits in
exchange for a 10-year suspension of their collective bargaining
agreement (CBA).
</P>
<P>
"We need a week before PAL can get back to normal, but I asked
PAL management to do it within three days and they told me they'll
try their best," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there won't be any need for a referendum among PAL
employees to ratify the agreement, noting that "a great majority
of PALEA officials have agreed to save PAL by accepting
management's package of benefits."
</P>
<P>
"Finally, there's an agreement. This could be the start of good
labor-management relations," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said both PAL management and
the labor unions had agreed that after the ratification of the
management-labor accord this week, PAL would likely resume its
flights by October 7.
</P>
<P>
The debt-ridden and strike-crippled PAL ceased operations at
midnight last Wednesday after the labor unions rejected the
co-ownership scheme offered by the management.
</P>
<P>
According to Zamora, the management-labor accord calls for an
ownership-sharing scheme that will give each employee 60,000
shares in the airline, and the retention of their medical benefits
that would include their families and relatives.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said the agreement also calls for the retention of the
majority of PAL's employees without any salary cuts, with a
special voluntary retirement package being offered by the
management for those who will not be re-hired.
</P>
<P>
Zamora, who met earlier with PAL Chairman Lucio Tan and
representatives of the Securities and Exchange Commission, said
PAL will fly 22 planes for its domestic and international routes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
