<HEADLINE> NZ Governor General Meets Chinese Senior Party Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Governor
General Michael Hardie Boys met here Monday with Wei Jianxing, one
of the top officials of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
Wei, member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau
of the CPC Central Committee, said that although China and New
Zealand are far apart geographically, the friendly exchange
between the two peoples goes back to ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Wei, who also is a member of the Secretariat of the CPC Central
Committee, is here on an official good-will visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
The late Rewi Alley, a great son of the New Zealand people,
made an important contribution to the cause of revolution and
construction of the Chinese people and to the cause of world
peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wei noted that since the two countries established diplomatic
ties 26 years ago, their bilateral relations have developed
remarkably thanks to joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese side hopes that the two countries will bring a
healthy and steadily-growing Sino-New Zealand relationship into
the next century," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wei briefed Boys on China's policy of reform and opening up,
the current economic situation in China and the recent anti-flood
struggle of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Boys said Rewi Alley has become a bridge of Sino-New Zealand
friendship.
</P>
<P>
He also praised the people of Chinese origin in New Zealand for
their important contributions to the social development of the
country.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand values friendly relations of cooperation with
China," Boys stressed.
</P>
<P>
During the past four days in New Zealand, Wei had extensive
contacts with personages of various circles, briefing them about
China's foreign policy and domestic construction, and exchanging
views with them on the Sino-New Zealand relations, China's
construction of democracy and the legal system, and its
anti-corruption struggle.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with New Zealand Minister of Foreign Affairs and
Trade Don Mckinnon, Wei said China is a steadfast force for
safeguarding peace and stability in the region and in the world as
well.
</P>
<P>
"China concentrates its efforts on economic construction. It
needs a long-term international environment of peace," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with Douglas Graham, New Zealand minister of
justice and attorney-general, Wei said the exchange and
cooperation between the judicial and supervisory departments of
the two countries had yielded positive results. He said China
would like to develop and strengthen such friendly exchange and
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At his meeting with Helen Clark, leader of the New Zealand
Labor Party, Wei expressed appreciation for the contribution her
party has made to the promotion of Sino-New Zealand relations.
</P>
<P>
He said the CPC desires to increase contacts with all of New
Zealand's political parties, including the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
Wei and his entourage arrived in Wellington Sunday after
visiting Auckland and Rotorua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
