<HEADLINE> Slovakia's Ruling Party Loses Majority in General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Slovak Prime Minister Vladimir
Meciar's Movement for Democratic Slovakia lost its parliamentary
majority in Saturday's election, giving a four-party opposition
coalition a chance to take power, preliminary results on Sunday
showed.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results announced by the central electoral
commission showed Meciar's ruling HZDS collected 27 percent of the
votes. Combined with another ruling party, the Slovak National
Party, which got 9.07 percent of the vote, Meciar will get only 57
seats in the 150-seat new parliament, 19 short of a parliamentary
majority.
</P>
<P>
The four opposition parties will occupy the remaining 93
seats. Of that, the Slovak Democratics' Alliance won 42 seats with
26.33 percent of the poll, the Party of Democratic Left of
Slovakia won 23 seats with 14.66 percent of the vote, the
Hungarian Coalition Party, and the Party of Civic Understanding
won 15 and 13 seats with 9.12 and 8.01 percent of the vote
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the four parties met hours after the announcement of
the results, signaling a willingness to form a new
administration. They made it clear that none of them will form a
coalition with Meciar's HZDS.
</P>
<P>
Under Slovakia's Constitution, the parliament with a term of
four years is the sole and top legislative body of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election was the second after Slovakia declared its
independence in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
