<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges S. African States to Wipe Out Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA) Monday called on Southern African
countries to learn from each other in their endeavor to eradicate
poverty.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, ECA Director Robert Okello
said the region's capacity to achieve sustainable development
will increase if poverty is eradicated.
</P>
<P>
he said development efforts should not be left to the
government alone, and urged the private sector to join to promote
development of their countries.
</P>
<P>
Globalization will never be achieved if the developed nations
continue to marginalize Africa, Okello noted.
</P>
<P>
He said Africa has lagged behind in development because it is
usually left out of the development programs by the Western
countries.
</P>
<P>
However, South African High Commissioner to Zambia Themba
Thabethe said Africa has failed to develop because of people's
attitude.
</P>
<P>
Although Africa has enough resources, Africans fail to plan
for the future development of their continent, Thabethe said.
</P>
<P>
The ECA will host the fifth meeting of inter-governmental
committee of experts for Southern Africa development in Lusaka
here next Monday. 
</P>
