<HEADLINE> Hunan Commemorates Death of Tan Sitong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,500
representatives of all circles in central China's Hunan Province
gathered today in the city of Liuyang, hometown of Tan Sitong, to
cherish the memory of this great reformer who sacrificed 100 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Some of Tan's relatives also came here today to attend a
ceremony marking the re-opening of Tan's former residence and the
unveiling of a new bronze statue of Tan.
</P>
<P>
Tan, a scholar in Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), devoted his life to
the 1898 Reform Movement, which was put down by the feudal
diehards led by Empress Dowager Cixi. Tan and five others were
killed on September 28, 1898.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 experts and scholars from China, Japan, the
United States and Australia have arrived in Liuyang to attend
tomorrow's symposium commemorating the 100th anniversary of the
1898 Reform Movement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
