<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Labor Edges Ahead of Ruling Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Labor Party
has edged ahead of the ruling coalition in a latest opinion poll
going into the final week of the election campaign, but polling in
marginal seats shows Australia could have a hung parliament after
Saturday's election.
</P>
<P>
The Bulletin poll taken over the weekend puts support for Labor
at 50.5 percent and the coalition at 49.5 percent, the Australian
Associated Press said Monday.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time Labor has taken the lead in the Bulletin
poll, and it means that Labor is ahead of the coalition in
Australia's four major polls.
</P>
<P>
The survey of more than 2,000 voters found the coalition's
primary vote had dropped by three points over the past week, down
to 40 percent, while Labor's had risen by two points to 39
percent.
</P>
<P>
One Nation was polling at 7 percent, the Australian Democrats
at 8 percent, the Greens at 3 percent and only 2 percent of voters
were still undecided.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the poll results, the Labor national secretary,
the party's most senior strategist, Gray Gray said Labor would
have to pull off the biggest political comeback in the country's
history to win Saturday's election.
</P>
<P>
According to Gray, Labor needs to win 27 more seats to win the
federal election, "it is a difficult task, and it's never been
done before... the task before us is the biggest campaign task
ever put before an opposition."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister John Howard also said he had
contemplated the risk of losing the election because of his push
for tax reform including the goods and services tax (GST).
</P>
<P>
He said the GST is a big political gamble, and he has no idea
if the Liberals would forgive him if he lost power this weekend,
he told ABC-TV. 
</P>
</TEXT>
