<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demining Virtually Comes to Halt in Angola: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- As a renewal of war looms up
in Angola, the work of removing land mines has virtually stopped
in the country, an Angolan minister said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Assistance and Social Reintegration Albino Malungo
noted that because of the frequent military activities of the
opposition National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA), only eight out of nineteen demining teams are now in
operation across the country.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government had set up 18 resident demining teams
plus a mobile one under the active support of the international
organizations, the minister disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Malungo said, UNITA fighters have been planting new
mines in many areas, for this the European Union has threatened
to cut off its assistance to Angola in the field of demining.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the situation, Malungo said, "things remain more or
less the same as every month, seven or eight people are injured
by mines."
</P>
<P>
Apart from the United States, Norway and Sweden are the major
providers of assistance, the Angolan minister said, adding that
they either directly help the Angolan government in removing land
mines and training technicians or through their non-government
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the U.N. indicated that over 10 million mines
were planted throughout Angola during the 30 years of civil war,
mainly in the agricultural provinces.
</P>
<P>
To reverse the situation, Malungo urged the international
community to take effective measures to force UNITA President
Jonas Savimbi "to demilitarize his forces and renounce his stand
for war." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Will Not Suffer Fresh Currency Crisis, Says Kim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 28 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung said here Monday that it is impossible for his nation to
suffer another foreign exchange currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kim told a press conference his government will take measures
to boost the economy at the expense of expanding the money supply
and widening the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
"While continuing to pursue fast and effective reforms, the
government will try to overcome the recession by taking
economy-boosting measures," Kim said.
</P>
<P>
The government will expand the money supply and fiscal spending
at the expense of incurring a wider budget deficit, and at the
same time, prop-up domestic consumption and lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government has decided to supply 8.5 trillion
won (some 6.3 billion U.S. dollars) in housing loans and another
six trillion won (about 4.4 billion U.S. dollars) to boost
consumption of durable goods.
</P>
<P>
The economy-boosting programs are supported by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), from which South Korea borrowed
58 billion U.S. dollars after it was gripped by a financial crisis
spurred by corporate failures and bad loans of financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed with the IMF to increase the budget deficit to
five percent of the gross domestic product (GDP)," Kim said.
</P>
<P>
Facing increasingly stronger challenges due to the growing
economic woes and the political standoff between the ruling and
opposition parties, Kim expressed strong confidence in the
strength of the South Korean economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the restructuring and economy-boosting measures will
begin to take effect in reviving the economy as of next year.
</P>
<P>
"The economy will never shrink any further, but will only pick
up from now on," a confident Kim said.
</P>
<P>
South Korean foreign exchange reserves reached a record-high 44
billion U.S. dollars last month while the current account surplus
grew. Interest rates, foreign exchange rates and inflation were
stabilized.
</P>
<P>
"In a nutshell, there is no possibility that we could face
another foreign currency crisis," the president said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Kim pressed the nation's family-owned conglomerates,
or chaebols, to speed up their restructuring process.
</P>
<P>
The chaebols must abide by their promise, he said, in an
apparent reference to the chaebols' agreement with the government
to save money by merging their redundant subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
"If not, the government will advise lenders to stop providing
new loans and withdraw those which have already been extended,"
Kim added.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed with the IMF last December for a 58
billion U.S. dollar bailout package, South Korea, once the 11th
economy in the world, has to restructure its economy and open
markets this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- There has been gradual revival of tourism in
Israel since this spring, local newspaper Haaretz quoted Israeli
Central Bureau of Statistics as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists entering Israel has increased by 2
percent a month for the past five months. Some 184,700 tourists
arrived in August.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Last week's decision by the U.S. Congress to
sharply increase the number of foreigners given visas for work in
America's high-tech industry will not cause a brain drain from
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper The Jerusalem Post on Monday quoted leaders of
Israeli high-tech industry as saying that there are plenty of
high-tech jobs in Israel, and wages in this field are not
significantly different from those in the U.S.. Therefore, there
is no reason to believe a brain drain will occur.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The privatization of Israel Discount Bank may
have to be postponed due to the international financial crisis
and the damage it has caused to several of the bidders.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Haaretz Monday quoted banking sources as saying
that another issue, which may lead some of the bidders to
withdraw, is their unhappiness with the conditions the Israeli
Central Bank has placed on the sale. These include forbidding the
new owners to distribute dividends from the sale of Discount's
assets.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Total Egyptian exports of cotton during the fourth
successive week has amounted to 34,630 tonnes, the equivalent of
693,000 Kantars, valued at 260.2 million Egyptian pounds (76.5
million U.S. dollars), Monday's Egyptian daily "Al Akhbar"
reported.
</P>
<P>
Cotton was exported to 28 different countries of the world. The
first ranks were occupied by Switzerland, Italy, Germany,
Australia, Turkey, the U.S. and India.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Algeria have reached an agreement under
which the Egyptian Aluminum Company will export 5000 metric tonnes
of aluminum ingots and bars to an Algerian enterprise, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The deal will be effected on five installments, starting from
next February and ending December 1999 at a total value of 9
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia's tourist revenues during the first nine
months of this year reached 1.1 billion dinars (1 billion
U.S. dollars), an increase of 7.4 percent as compared to the
corresponding period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The growing revenue was attributed to the increase in touristic
nights in hotels during the period, a rise of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Minister of Energy Habibollah Bitaraf said
that his ministry will sell bonds and obtain loans from abroad to
balance the deficit in this year's budget, the official news
Agency IRNA reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
It added that the ministry plans to get 300 million dollars in
loans this year to cover much of its needs of foreign exchange. He
said that the bonds would be offered for public contribution as
from mid-October, but failed to reveal the issuing value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
