<HEADLINE> Security Situation Worsening in Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The security situation in
Mogadishu and its surrounding areas is worsening as a new wave of
killing, robbing, looting and kidnaping began in recent days,
despite efforts to restore law and order in the Somali capital.
</P>
<P>
At least five people were killed and more than seven others
were wounded in separate armed clashes in Mogadishu Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
One of those clashes took place between armed militiamen
supporting Hussein Mohamed Aidid based in Hosh camp of the former
Hunter Base and those belonging to the militia leader Muse Sudi
Yalahow in Medina district.
</P>
<P>
During the confrontation, three people including one of the
militiamen were killed and a stray mortar round exploded,
wounding three others including two children.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen from both sides have pit stiff resistance
against each other and each side had retreated to its former
defensive position although at least six battle wagons from both
sides were involved in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Some reports said the fighting was touched off after the
militiamen of Mise Sudi launched an attack on Aidid's men in an
attempt to dislodge them from the area.
</P>
<P>
But other reports had it that Aidid's men provoked the attack
by "tryi6@Q="B-
-"!:#+$\+3+$.]X:ion" to deploy a
new police force supporting Mogadishu's disputed administration,
a charge denied by commander of the police force, Colonel Abdi
Hassan Awale Qeybdid.
</P>
<P>
In another incident, two people were killed and two others
were wounded when armed clashes had erupted between rival
militiamen in Bermuda area at the heart of the city, resulting
from the abduction of a lady there.
</P>
<P>
The lady was riding on a Volkswagen in Bermuda when her car
was intercepted and she was taken away to an unknown place in the
vicinity.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic courts and the recently-announced administration
have been doing their best to demobilize hundreds of militiamen.
</P>
<P>
However, the threat for further clashes is still eminent
unless it is defused and intervened by the clan elders of the
area, observers here say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
