<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brown Vows No Change in Britain's Economic Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLACKPOOL, Britain, September 28 (Xinhua) -- British finance
minister Gordon Brown vowed on Monday that he will keep his
economic policies unchanged so as to avoid boom and bust
instability caused by short-term spending.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the annual Labor Party Conference in Blackpool,
a coastal city in northwestern England, Brown said he will try to
keep inflation low and prevent short-term economic growth that
will lead to long-term reduction in investment.
</P>
<P>
"It is because of our commitment to long-term stability, even
more essential at a time of world instability, that from this
government there will be no U-turns," the chancellor of the
exchequer said.
</P>
<P>
Brown has been under pressure from domestic manufacturers to
boost short-term spending and growth since a strong pound is
threatening their business.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Brown warned that his first task had to be to
set a credible long-term platform in pace because they had learned
from the Conservative government's mistakes that every time the
British economy started to grow, it quickly overheated and ran
into inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
He cited as an example the former Conservative government's
short-sighted economic policies in the late 1980s that led to boom
and bust and finally to recession.
</P>
<P>
"It was short-termism and the betrayal of the country's
long-term needs that -- in spite of their talk of long-term
resolution -- led Mrs. Thatcher 10 years ago to inflate the
economy, cut taxes, go for short-term growth, and brought in 15
percent interest rates, and the loss of one million manufacturing
jobs in 1990," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Labor's economic competence, its iron
resolution and its prudence for a purpose, was hard earned and
hard won, "and we will not sacrifice it for today's standing
ovations, tomorrow's headlines, next week's easy slogans, or next
month's false solution." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
