<HEADLINE> Citroen Joint Venture Launches New Car in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Dongfeng-Citroen
Automobile Co. Ltd, one of the largest automotive manufacturers in
China, launched a new model car in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The new sedan is the third generation of the "Fukang" model
that Dongfeng-Citroen has developed in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Dongfeng-Citroen said that the new "Fukang 988"
car is designed specially for the taxi and company-car market. It
changed the look of the earlier model by adding a luggage
compartment to the back, installing a more powerful engine
and utilizing an Italian-designed chassis.
</P>
<P>
According to local automotive experts, the new model
demonstrates that the largest Sino-French joint venture is
stepping up its competitiveness in the car market of China.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture in central China has the annual capacity of
150,000 Citroen cars, a make originally designed for family use in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
For the first time ever in China, individuals are expected to
buy more cars than organizations this year.
</P>
<P>
However, experts say that the supply and variety of family-use
cars are so limited that the market remains unstable.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, major car manufacturers in China are increasing
their presence in the business-car market, where there is a lower
risk than the family-car market.
</P>
<P>
The First Automobile Works Group (FAW), one of the top three
automotive manufactures in China, is increasing the output of its
"Red Flag" business car, and the Shanghai Volkswagen
Corp. launched the Santana 2000 GSi luxury car earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
One buyer of the new Citroen 988 car said that at the same price
level, he would prefer better performance of brand names.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet customer demand for better performance,
Chinese automotive manufacturers are applying new technologies
such as air bags and power-steering in their products.
</P>
<P>
Dongfeng-Citroen conducted the first car-crash tests in the
history of the country's automotive industry in June.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiaoyu, deputy director of the State Bureau of Machinery
Industry, said at the launching ceremony for the new model
today that market competition will push Dongfeng-Citroen and other
Chinese automotive manufacturers to create more new products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
