<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Fishery Commission Opens New Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The 26th session of the
Asia-Pacific Fishery Commission (APFIC) opened here today,
with representatives from 20 member countries and two
international organizations attending the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will focus its discussions on current problems
facing the fishery industry in the Asia-Pacific region, the
achievements made by the APFIC and its future direction.
</P>
<P>
Fish has long been a traditional part of the Asian diet and the
fishing industry there has developed rapidly.
</P>
<P>
China also has rapidly developed in this field, said Zhuo
Youzhan, director of the Fishery Bureau of the Ministry of
Agriculture. In 1997, the country's aquatic-products output
reached 36 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Zhuo, also president of the current session, acknowledged that
China's fishing industry still faces some problems, such as
declining resources in offshore areas and worsening sea pollution.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this session may offer an opportunity for China
to cooperate with other Asia-Pacific countries in the fishing
industry.
</P>
<P>
In the past week, the APFIC hosted two other Beijing
international seminars on issues related to the fishing industry.
</P>
<P>
APFIC, an affiliate of the Food and Agriculture Organization of
the United Nations, now has 20 member countries, including China.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
