<HEADLINE> 13 Detained for Illegal Assembly in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Police Monday detained
13 people including 10 university students for taking part in an
illegal assembly in Johor Baharu, southern Malaysia, the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
The illegal assembly in support of sacked deputy prime minister
Anwar Ibrahim's reform movement was attended by some 100 people.
</P>
<P>
Police broke up the assembly and detained the students who
refused to obey police orders, Bernama said. Three women were also
detained in a car which carried anti-government pamphlets.
</P>
<P>
The detained were taken to the Central Police Station in Johor
Baharu, some 370 kilometers south of here, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was sacked as deputy prime minister and finance minister
on September 2 and expelled from the ruling United Malays National
Organization (UMNO) a day later for "low morals."
</P>
<P>
He was arrested by police at his house here on September 20 for
calling an illegal assembly earlier that day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
