<HEADLINE> Hiroshima Governor Protests at U.S. Subcritical Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Yuzan Fujita, governor of
Japan's Hiroshima Prefecture, on Monday sent a letter to
U.S. President Bill Clinton, protesting against a subcritical
nuclear test the United States conducted Saturday, Kyodo News
reported.
</P>
<P>
Fujita said in the letter that he was "greatly angered and deeply
disappointed" by the test, the fourth of its kind conducted by the
United States in Nevada since July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The governor urged the United States to immediately stop all
nuclear tests and asked for U.S. cooperation in achieving global
nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, meanwhile, Japanese top government spokesman Hiromu
Nonaka told reporters that it is regrettable that the United
States conducted the test at a time when India and Pakistan showed
resolve to sign the global nuclear test ban treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
