<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search for U.S. Bomber Wreckage in Guangxi Progresses Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A group of military experts
from the United States set off early this morning for Mao'er Hill
in Xing'an County near this tourist resort in south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region to take part in the third attempt
to find the wreckage of a U.S. B-24 bomber that crashed in 1944.
</P>
<P>
This search has so far produced a pistol case, two bone
fragments and a number of bullets, buttons and coins believed to
belong to the B-24 bomber which went down in action against the
Japanese fleet during World War ll.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the search party Captain Todd Goeheler said that the
search has been progressing "very smoothly" and the close
cooperation between the two sides will have a positive influence
on Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
The 11-member team composed of mountain climbers,
anthropologists, and demolition and medical experts arrived at
Mao-er Hill on September 8 and began their search on September 15
after a few days of preparation including the clearing of paths at
the venue.
</P>
<P>
Four platforms have been built on the mountain side and the
team began at the bottom by marking key areas with small blue
flags and white cloth ribbons after careful inspection.
</P>
<P>
Each morning at half past seven, the team headed out of their
camps for the search site and returned at four in the afternoon
after a brief lunch at the site.
</P>
<P>
By September 26, the team has finished searching at the fourth
platform and most of the third platform.
</P>
<P>
Goeheler said that people in the U.S. are very much concerned
with this search and the team reports to the departments
responsible in the U.S. everyday, and will eventually report to
the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Congress is satisfied with the team's efforts, said
Goeheler, who also expressed his appreciation for the facilities
provided by the Chinese government, local governments at various
levels and Chinese workers.
</P>
<P>
He said that to avoid bad weather the team selected the best
time to search here as September and October. Unfortunately, the
drought in the northern part of Guangxi resulted in a shortage of
drinking water on the mountain, and the Chinese have helped
take water up to the camps and organized workers, and medical,
safety and other supporting services for the team.
</P>
<P>
The first search began on January 13, 1997, and the second was
conducted between October and November last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
