<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Award for Small, Medium-Sized Businesses Launched in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- An award was launched here
Monday by the Hong Kong Productivity Council (HKPC) and the Hong
Kong General Chamber of Commerce (HKGCC) to recognize the
achievements by small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong SME Award is funded by the Services Support Fund
of the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) and is also supported by 14 organizations and trade
associations.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the launch of the award at a press conference,
Thomas Tang, executive director of HKPC, said that SMEs account
for 98 percent of Hong Kong's business establishments and employ
67 percent of the local working population.
</P>
<P>
"Their development and performance are therefore crucial to the
well-being of the Hong Kong company," Tang said.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the Asian financial turmoil, Hong Kong's businesses
are facing some difficulties at present, Tang said. However,
some SMEs still have achieved good results.
</P>
<P>
They will be singled out as examples for other SMEs and through
the SME Award, their experience for success will be shared among
other SMEs, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
Companies employing less than 100 people in manufacturing and
firms employing less than 50 people in service are considered as
SMEs and there are now some 300,000 SMEs in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong SME Award is the first award tailor-made for
local SMEs to identify success models to spearhead Hong Kong's
continued growth and competitiveness, said Vincent Li, general
manager of the Business Enhancement Services Division of HKPC and
member of the SME Award Working Committee.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, the SME Award consists of two categories: The
New SME Award for SMEs of less than 3 years in operation and the
Best Managed SME Award for SMEs of over 3 years in operation.
</P>
<P>
Winners will have an opportunity to build up their business
networking and increase their credit facilities by up to 20
million HK dollars (2.56 million U.S. dollars) with most
preferential interest from East Asia Heller Limited, the sole
sponsor for the award, he said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Award winners will be invited to take part in a
study mission as Award Ambassadors to share their success stories
with SMEs in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, HKPC has given recognition to the outstanding
achievements of Hong Kong businesses with the Hong Kong Award for
Industry. The Hong Kong Award for Services was subsequently
introduced in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nile Basin States Seek Joint Development Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Ministers from Nile
basin countries have agreed at a meeting in Tanzania's northern
town of Arusha to carry out a joint strategy in developing the
region sustainably.
</P>
<P>
According to Tanzanian Minister of Water Mussa Juma Nkhangaa,
the ministers have reached agreement on a number of issues such
as securing investment in water resources, raising awareness of
the potential of natural resources, and utilizing water resources
equitably in the region.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was made at a two-day meeting last week in
Arusha, which was attended by water ministers from Ethiopia,
Egypt, Sudan, Rwanda, Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania and a senior
government official from Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Two other Nile basin cooperation partners -- the Democratic
Republic of Congo and Eritrea, failed to send delegates.
</P>
<P>
The ministers have also underscored the importance of
developing infrastructure which will create wealth and employment
opportunities leading to the elimination of poverty in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, the United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
and the Canadian International Development Agency have pledged
support for the development strategy, the Daily News reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nkhangaa, who is also the current chairman of the Nile Basin
Council of Ministers, said that the water ministers will meet
again early next year in Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa to make a
follow-up on the implementation of the strategy before a summit
of the Nile Basin state leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Chancellor Favors Joining Single Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLACKPOOL, Britain, September 28 (Xinhua) -- British finance
minister Gordon Brown said here on Monday that Britain will not
rule out joining the single currency as its economic interests
lies in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Labor Party Conference at this northwestern
coastal city, the Chancellor of the Exchequer said that at a time
when the balance of risks in the world economy is shifting, "a
Britain facing up to the challenges must work with other countries
and implement a reform agenda for global stability and growth."
</P>
<P>
"A Britain which sees that our national economic interest lies
in Europe, that is a zone of stability and growth will reject the
isolationism of the Conservative Party, and refuse to rule out
constructive engagement, particularly on the single currency, on
the basis of ideological dogma."
</P>
<P>
So far Britain has stated it would not join the first wave of
the single currency in the current parliament that ends in 2001
under strong domestic pressure.
</P>
<P>
The European Monetary Union will be launched on January 1, 1999
and 11 out of the 15 EU members have qualified to join the single
currency at the first wave.
</P>
<P>
He said the task of the British government was to make the
country equipped for every challenge of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
Brown also said that to ensure global coordination and a better
equipped IMF and World Bank, the British government will put
forward a proposal at next week's IMF meeting in Washington on a
new and pioneering global code of conduct for social policy.
</P>
<P>
He would travel to the IMF on Tuesday personally to argue for
policies for stability, growth and fairness to ensure that our
obligations to the unemployed and the vulnerable are met in every
part of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
