<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's External Trade Declines in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's
re-exports, domestic exports and imports declined in August over a
year earlier. But the overall pace of decline was less severe than
that of July.
</P>
<P>
This is revealed in the external trade figures for August 1998
released Monday by the Census and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The value of total exports (comprising re-exports and domestic
exports) decreased by 8.0 percent in August 1998 over a year
earlier to 119.1 billion HK dollars (15.3 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Within this total, the value of re-exports decreased by 7.6
percent to 101.6 billion HK dollars (13.0 billion U.S. dollars),
while the value of domestic exports fell by 10.3 percent to 17.5
billion HK dollars (2.2 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of imports decreased by 14.2 percent in August 1998
over a year earlier to 119.9 billion HK dollars (15.4 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
A visible trade deficit of only 0.7 billion HK dollars (89.7
million U.S. dollars), equivalent to 0.6 percent of the value of
imports, was recorded in August 1998. This was distinctly smaller
than the corresponding value recorded in the same month in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest trade statistics, a Government
Secretariat spokesman said that the disruption in air cargo
handling services at the new airport in the early part of August
could have exacerbated the rate of decline in the trade aggregates
last month, though perhaps rather less significantly than in July.
</P>
<P>
But in large part, the weak performance of merchandise exports
in August was due to the continued plunge in import demand in the
Asian markets, as well as the ongoing shift in the structure of
external trade towards offshore trading, the spokesman noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
