<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Agricultural Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- In the past two decades,
China's agriculture has grown rapidly, contributing a great
deal to the development of the national economy, according to the
State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
Economic reforms in rural areas have brought more growth in
agriculture, a better industry and employment structure, and a
better standard of living for farmers, the SSB says.
</P>
<P>
In that period, annual average growth has stayed at 6.7 percent
and annual grain output growth at 2.7 percent, well ahead of
population growth for the period.
</P>
<P>
The forest industry output has grown 1.9-fold, animal husbandry
5-fold, and the fishery business 8.2-fold.
</P>
<P>
There has also been an improvement in the rural industrial mix,
with the proportion of farming in the rural economy down 44.2
percentage points since 1978, and the proportion of industry and
services up. In 1997, the industrial sector had the dominant role
in the rural economy, accounting for 62.9 percent of output value.
</P>
<P>
Chinese farmers now have a better life, thanks to the reform
policies since 1978, with average per capita income in rural areas
going to 2,090 yuan in 1997 from 134 yuan in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The SSB says that the government's policies have been correct,
giving agriculture, especially grain production, top priority,
protecting farmers' interests and implementing the household
contract responsibility system.
</P>
<P>
The problems in agriculture are the low technology level,
vulnerability to natural disasters, the unreasonable employment
structure and resource distribution, and low incomes for farmers.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
