<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Was Key in Unmasking Iraqi Arms: Inspector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Israel was quietly
instrumental over the last four years in helping U.N. arms
inspectors uncover how Iraq conceals its weapons of mass
destruction, local daily Haaretz reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the paper, Scott Ritter, who had
been member of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
disarmament in Iraq, said he made many trips to Israel during his
tenure as arms inspector. "From 1994 to 1998, I was there a lot,"
Ritter said.
</P>
<P>
Ritter quit his post last month in protest against what he felt
was U.S. government's inaction in carrying out the Iraqi arms
inspections.
</P>
<P>
He told Haaretz that he had the idea of soliciting Israel's
assistance with the inspections because the UNSCOM was not getting
adequate assistance from the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA)
and other U.S. government officials.
</P>
<P>
Ritter praised the professionalism Israel showed in working
with the UNSCOM over the last several years. He said that Israel
was taking seriously a U.N. resolution passed after the 1991 Gulf
War calling on all member countries to work closely with the
UNSCOM to disarm Iraq of its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
"I can honestly say that if it weren't for Israel, the Special
Commission would not have been able to carry out the
anti-concealment effort," Ritter said.
</P>
<P>
"It's Tel Aviv that can be hit by these missiles and not New
York city, and we were actually, frankly speaking, a little
dismayed with the lack of intensity, the lack of enthusiasm that
emanated from Washington, D.C. on this issue. The (U.S.) treated
(concealment) more as an academic exercise, and I thought Israel
treated it as it is -- a matter of life and death," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ritter also blamed the CIA for instigating the current
investigation of the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) into
whether he engaged in espionage by providing sensitive
information to Israel. Ritter ridiculed the investigation as
"outrageous."
</P>
<P>
First, he indicated that the idea to cooperate with Israel was
authorized by former UNSCOM chief Rolf Ekeus and each trip was
approved by his superiors.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, he said, he informed the U.S. government of "every
step." Thirdly, being a U.N. official, he had no CIA security
clearance, and therefore even if he wanted to, he would have no
access to top-secret U.S. documents, a point which he says the CIA
recognizes.
</P>
<P>
Ritter insisted that the CIA was motivated more by jealousy
since the UNSCOM had a better working relationship with Israeli
officials than American officials.
</P>
<P>
Since leaving his post last month, Ritter has appeared before
Congressional panels to complain about how the U.S. government
told the UNSCOM not to conduct arms inspection in the last couple
of months in order to avoid confrontation with Iraq. The
U.S. government sharply denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
The interview with Haaretz, which will be published in full
details on Tuesday, is the first time that Ritter addressed in
depth UNSCOM's ties with Israel and its link to the FBI
investigation.
</P>
<P>
The former arms inspector stressed that it was the UNSCOM
tapping Israeli expertise in dealing with cells of militant
groups, not the UNSCOM being used by Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Israel was a fair player on all of this. It was extremely
responsible," Ritter said, adding that "I didn't receive any money
from Israel... I got a shake of the hand, a pat on the back."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
