<HEADLINE> South Korea's Partisan Contention Escalates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The political contention in
South Korea has escalated over the nomination of prime minister
and the issue of corruption at a time when the nation is in
desperate need of concerted efforts to overcome economic woes.
</P>
<P>
Confrontation between the ruling and opposition parties
overwhelmed ever since President Kim Dae-jung was sworn in on
February 25 this year, when the opposition began boycotting the
National Assembly (parliament) to reject President Kim's
nomination of Kim Jong-pil as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The political confrontation has worsened when the opposition
Grand National Party (GNP) took to the streets since last week in
protest at what it called the ruling camp's "politically-
motivated scheme to weaken and break up the opposition" by use of
the prosecutors' investigation of corrupt politicians, mostly in
the opposition party.
</P>
<P>
After the GNP's rejection of the nomination, the ruling camp
stepped up its regrouping by recruiting legislators from the
opposition in a bid to dominate the 299-member parliament, in
which the GNP had 161 seats at that time.
</P>
<P>
The opposition lost its majority in parliament last month after
12 lawmakers defected to the ruling coalition of the National
Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and the United Liberal Democrats
(ULD).
</P>
<P>
The GNP, which has been boycotting the 100-day regular session
of the parliament due to open on September 10, once threatened to
make its 113 lawmakers resign in protest against the anti-
corruption drive.
</P>
<P>
GNP leader Lee Hoi-chang said "I will fight strongly to end the
politically motivated scheme to destroy the opposition. I am
determined to fight to my end."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Kim and his ruling camp have reiterated
their commitment to pushing ahead with the drive against
corruption, saying that there will be neither democracy nor
economic progress wherever there is corruption.
</P>
<P>
"The government is conducting the work of eradicating
corruption and injustice with a firm determination, and I will set
an example for the nation," said President Kim, who is NCNP's top
leader.
</P>
<P>
The rival political parties are fundamentally at odds over
whether state prosecutors are now conducting the probe of corrupt
politicians and others impartially irrespective of their different
party affiliations.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors are probing into the behaviors of some 200 people,
including politicians and ranking public servants, as well as
executives of banking institutions and industrial firms.
</P>
<P>
It is seen as a telling blow to the opposition that the
prosecution found that the GNP had used leading figures of the
Office of National Tax Administration to collect huge sums of
money in donations to support its presidential candidate Lee
Hoi-chang during last year's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
The ruling camp has reaffirmed its determination not to engage
in any dialogue or negotiations with the GNP unless the opposition
party apologizes unconditionally for illegal fund-raising through
the National Tax Administration during the presidential
campaigning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
