<HEADLINE> Industrial Capacity Utilization Drops in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Manufacturers Association
of Nigeria (MAN) has said that the average industrial capacity
utilization of the country dropped to 27.8 percent in the first
half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Punch newspaper Monday quoted MAN as saying in its
half-year economic review that the capacity utilization recorded
29.4 percent and 34 percent in the first and last half of last
year respectively. The review covered the period from January to
June this year.
</P>
<P>
MAN noted that virtually all manufacturing sub-sectors
registered a decline, including the food, beverages and tobacco
sub-sectors, where expectations of better performance were high
early this year.
</P>
<P>
Nominal manufacturing output declined from 40.05 billion Naira
(about 445 million U.S. Dollars) in the first half of last year
to 30.65 billion Naira (about 340 million Dollars), a substantial
drop of 23.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Total manufacturing investment amounted to 1.47 billion Naira
(about 16 million Dollars) in the period under review, compared
to 2.26 billion and 2.74 billion Naira in the first and second
half of last year respectively.
</P>
<P>
The association attributed the unimpressive industrial
performance during the period to the energy crisis which has
persisted since last February.
</P>
<P>
The protracted scarcity of diesel, fuel and kerosene
interrupted the operations of some factories and forced some
others out of business, MAN added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
