<HEADLINE> Kaunda May Not Retire From Politics: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- There are growing fears in
the United National Independence Party (UNIP) that former
president Kenneth Kaunda may not retire as he intends to continue
with his political crusade, a Zambian national daily said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Government-owned Times of Zambia quoted some senior members of
the country's largest opposition party as saying at the weekend
that the party leader Kaunda is planning to ignore the October 4
deadline to honor a retirement deal with the Zambian government.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the state withdrew its charges of imprisonment of
treason against him in early June this year, Kaunda, who ruled
the country for 27 years and was defeated by incumbent President
Frederick Chiluba in 1991, declared that he would retire from
active party politics.
</P>
<P>
The 74-year old veteran politician was arrested last December
for alleged involvement in the country's foiled military coup in
October 1997.
</P>
<P>
The sources claimed that Kaunda may not take up the house the
government allocated to him last month as part of his retirement
benefits.
</P>
<P>
It is said that Kaunda and the government has concluded an
agreement under which he will get all his retirement benefits as
a former president on condition that he retires from active
politics.
</P>
<P>
However, he has not handed a letter of resignation to the
party secretary general as required by the party constitution if
he wants to retire before his term of office expires by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to force Kaunda to retire, the Zambian parliament
recently endorsed the Benefits of Former Presidents Amendment
Bill which states that a former president would lose his benefits
if he participates in active politics and the bill is now only
awaiting presidential assent to become law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
