<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Manpower Outflow Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The outflow of manpower in
Hong Kong slowed down to a decade-low rate in 1997 as the
successful transition has dispersed people's worries about
political uncertainty, according to a survey released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which tracks the latest development of manpower
movement in Hong Kong, shows that 0.54 percent of the total
workforce chose to emigrate in 1997, representing a significant
decrease from 0.82 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The figure is the lowest since 1988, according to the Hong Kong
Institute of Human Resource Management (IHRM), a non-profit
organization which conducts the survey annually.
</P>
<P>
Sara Cheung, research director of IHRM, said Monday: "Before
1997, people emigrated because they were uncertain about Hong
Kong's future. But after a smooth transition on July 1, fewer
people chose to leave."
</P>
<P>
More than 140 companies in a variety of industries participate
in the survey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
