<HEADLINE> Exhibition on Ancient Chinese Inventions Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Museum of
History, after its 23 years of establishment, moved to its
permanent home and staged its first exhibition -- "Heavenly
Creations - Gems of Ancient Chinese Inventions" Monday.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition was officially opened by Chief Executive Tung
Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, Tung said China, as one of the
great ancient civilizations, had long been renowned for her rich
historical and cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
"China's technological development dated back to early history,
and its extensiveness and far-reaching influences are unrivaled,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung believed that this exhibition provided a splendid
opportunity for the people of Hong Kong to have a better
understanding of the scientific and technological achievements, as
well as the diligence, wisdom and creativity of the great
scientists and fine craftsmen of ancient China.
</P>
<P>
This large-scale exhibition is jointly presented by the
Provisional Urban Council of Hong Kong and the National Museum of
Chinese History. It is open to the public on September 29 through
January 3, 1999. 
</P>
