<HEADLINE> Tokyo Share Prices Rise Despite Japan Leasing's Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher in
Tokyo on Monday despite the collapse of Japan Leasing Corp., a
nonbank affiliate of the ailing Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan
(LTCB).
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 185.53 points, or 1.35
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 13,909.37. The index
temporarily jumped nearly 400 points during the day.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, advanced 13.59 points or 1.29 percent to
1,063.52.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section was light at an estimated 370
million shares, almost unchanged from Friday.
</P>
<P>
LTCB was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Japan Leasing Corp. filed for court protection Sunday night
from its creditors, with debts totaling 2.18 trillion yen (about
16.1 billion U.S. dollars), the largest-ever amount seen in Japan
since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Traders suspect the Japanese government waged another round of
"price-keeping operations" by snapping up large amounts of Nikkei
index futures. This helped buoy shares across the board on the
cash market as investors filled their arbitrage positions.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,342 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outnumbered losers 778 to 370, with 143 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
