<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loans Helping Ease North China Province's Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Poverty alleviation project
of north China's Shanxi Province has been funded by the World Bank
since 1995, and local farmers have begun to benefit from 1.74
billion yuan (210 million US dollars) in spending, with 100
million U.S. dollars in World Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The project covers 5.55 million local people in some 5,770
villages, according to Zhang Qiuming, deputy director of the
Shanxi Provincial Finance Deparment, who is in charge of the
project.
</P>
<P>
He said the project includes rebuilding irrigation systems,
improving rural roads, and improving village water supplies, land
development, livestock raising and horticulture, and agricultural
processing.
</P>
<P>
So far, 850 million yuan (102 million US dollars) has been put
in, making up 47.8 percent of the planned total, 373 million yuan
(45 million US dollars) of which came from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, the money has been used to develop
7,200 ha. of Yellow River banks, terrace 11,300 ha. of hillsides,
and add 62,700 ha. of trees, and to raise more than 30,000 head of
livestock, build five township or village roads and provide
drinking water for 300,000 local people and more than 40,000
animals.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Zhang said, the development of low-yield land has
raised grain output and forestry and livestock projects have
helped change agricultural structure and increase farmers' income.
</P>
<P>
In the project areas the number of people in need has gone from
1.26 million in 1995 to 780,000.
</P>
<P>
The project has also helped improve local environment and
reduce soil erosion, demonstrating the need for the continued
development of the environment and agricultural production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
