<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Leasing Corp. Goes Under With Huge Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Japan Leasing Corp., one of
three nonbank affiliates of the ailing Long-Term Credit Bank of
Japan (LTCB), said Monday it has filed for court protection from
its creditors under the Corporate Rehabilitation Law.
</P>
<P>
Japan Leasing, the country's second largest nonbank financial
firm, effectively went bankrupt with debts of 2,180.3 billion yen
(about 16.1 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The bankruptcy is the largest in terms of debts in Japan since
the end of World War II, surpassing the previous biggest failure
of Crown Leasing Corp. in April last year with debts of 1,187.4
billion yen (about 8.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
"We had sought restructuring of our own, but some of our
creditors have moved to keep intact their claims on loans to us,
making it impossible for us to go through rehabilitation," Hiroaki
Okamoto, president of the company, told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
All of the board directors of the company will resign soon to
take responsibility for the collapse, he added.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi told reporters earlier in
the day that he wants the Japanese people, particularly those in
the financial markets and industry, to take the leasing company's
failure calmly.
</P>
<P>
"The government will ensure all measures to stabilize the
financial market. I would like to ask people to act in an orderly
manner," he said.
</P>
<P>
Market watchers, however, said the failure will inevitably deal
a telling blow to the already shaky financial industry.
</P>
<P>
The leasing company has about 165 creditors, including banks,
life insurance firms and financial institutions of the
agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
Japan Leasing, established in 1963 and with 20.2 billion yen
(about 14.8 million dollars) in capital, borrowed from financial
institutions and invested heavily in real estate during the
"bubble" economy of the latter half of the 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The burst of the bubble economy in the early 1990s left it with
a huge burden of accumulated debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
