<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction Starts on China's Fast Neutron Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- China began construction
today on its first fast neutron reactor power station, which is
scheduled to be completed by 2003, according to Li Zhongping,
deputy director of the China Fast Reactor Engineering Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Located in Fangshan County in southwestern Beijing, the Chinese
capital, the first pilot fast neutron reactor will generate a
thermal power of 65 MWt and an electric power of 20 MWe and will
be used as the base for building China's first commercial fast
neutron reactor power station in the early 21st century, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The reactor is believed to be more efficient, safer, and has a
higher utilization rate of uranium and is significant for China's
energy development in the next century, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
He said that it will raise the utilization rate of uranium from
around 1 percent in the existing pressurized water reactors to 60
to 70 percent in the new reactors.
</P>
<P>
China's Daya Bay and Qinshan nuclear power plants both use
pressurized water reactors and will continue to play a role in
meeting the country's energy needs, but large-scale development of
pressurized water reactors is difficult in China because of the
country's limited uranium reserves.
</P>
<P>
The main part of this reactor is scheduled to be completed by
December of next year and it will start trial power generating by
the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
China will need an equivalent of 1 billion tons of standard
coal by the middle of the next century, according to a report by
the Ministry of Science and Technology and the State Development
Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
China needs to develop its nuclear power generating capacity to
240 million kw by 2050, or 20 percent of its then national
electric power generating capacity, compared with the current one
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
