<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Boosted by Better Asian Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A rise in Asian markets and
a strong performance from key stocks helped the Australian share
market to a one percent gain after a day of modest trading Monday.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 28.2 points firmer at 2,591.6,
the all industrials climbed 49.2 points to 4,542.0 and the all
resources put on 11.3 points to 1,020.3.
</P>
<P>
The rise followed gains in both Japan's Nikkei, up 185.0 points
to 13,909.0, and Hong Kong's Hang Seng, 244.4 firmer at 7,946.0,
over the day.
</P>
<P>
But brokers noted that local volume for the day was only a
modest 245.7 million shares worth 862.7 million Australian dollars
(500.7 million U.S. dollars) with 464 rising stocks shading 462
falling and 338 steady.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said interest in the broad market was relatively flat
with trade in a few majors accounting for much of the gain in the
all ordinaries index.
</P>
<P>
But while National Australia Bank's volume was strong it was a
weaker performer in the banking sector as it managed to rise just
0.1 percent, or 2.2 Australian cents, to 21.03 Australian dollars,
the lowest rise of the major four Australian banks.
</P>
<P>
The banking index was firmer. It closed 45.2 higher at 5,566.5
points, as Commonwealth Bank of Australia climbed 24 cents to
19.89 Australian dollars, ANZ bank added 12.3 cents to 9.017
Australian dollars and Westpac bank moved up nine cents to 9.58
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The recent strength of the U.S. dollar gold price has
reportedly encouraged a surge in interest in the gold sector by
some funds, almost all of which are considerably underweight in
the sector after months of underperformance.
</P>
<P>
Consequently the gold index rallied 35.0 points, over three
percent, to 1,146.5 despite the spot price of bullion closing
294.45 U.S. dollars per fine ounce in Sydney, 0.20 U.S. dollars
weaker than Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
Resources sector leader BHP managed a five cent gain to 12.35
Australian dollars, after touching a high of 12.48 Australian
dollars, global miner Rio Tinto put on 23.5 cents to 20.20
Australian dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
