<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Firmer on Back of Rate Cut Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
closed stronger Monday, continuing to be influenced by speculation
of an interest rate cut in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Nick Volanakis, foreign exchange dealer at Australia's
Colonial State Bank, said the local currency shrugged off a
weakening in the Japanese yen and a fall in commodities.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 58.85 U.S. cents from 58.73
U.S. cents in Sydney at Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
It traded between 58.58 and 58.97 U.S. cents Monday and was
expected to trade above 59.00 U.S. cents overnight.
</P>
<P>
Sentiment on the market was slightly more positive, although
still uncertain of the outcome of the U.S. Federal Reserve's Open
Market Committee meeting (early Wednesday morning Australian
Eastern Standard Time).
</P>
<P>
Japan's banking crisis would continue to be a focus for the
market, especially after news that Japan Leasing Corp., an
affiliate of the troubled Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd., had
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
Volanakis said nervousness in the currency market surrounding
the Australian federal election on October 3 was due more to the
possibility of no clear mandate for the party elected, rather than
who wins.
</P>
<P>
"Someone like (Pauline Hanson's) One Nation (Party) getting the
balance of power or the (ruling) Liberals getting in with a small
margin and having difficulty getting its reforms through, would be
a negative," he said.
</P>
<P>
The local currency was buying 79.92 Japanese yen from 79.52 yen
last Friday and 0.9916 German marks from 0.9826 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
