<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Nations to Lift Sanctions Against Us: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar has said that the sanctions imposed on
Nigeria would be lifted soon following his discussions with top
leaders of Britain, the United States of America and France.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in capital Abuja Sunday from his six-day
visit to the three countries, the head of state said that "I am
happy we have achieved a lot," according to press reports Monday.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that Nigeria may soon get debt relief
from its Western creditors, saying that "we went to look for our
relief from the debt burden through the IMF, World Bank, Paris
and London clubs, and the feelers that we got were very positive
and a lot of groundwork has been done."
</P>
<P>
Abubakar told reporters that "first, I was in London where I
had meetings with the Prime Minister, who gave me all the support
to assist us in talking to all these bodies."
</P>
<P>
Then, he added, "I met Bill Clinton who also promised to do
all he can to assist us to resolve some of those problems, and
lastly yesterday (Friday), I met Chirac, who also promised to
continue what he was doing."
</P>
<P>
The French president assured the Nigerian leader that France
was backing the re-admission of Nigeria into the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Britain has already lifted the flight restrictions imposed on
Nigeria and the British Airways has commenced scheduled flights
to Lagos while Nigeria Airways has also announced plans to reopen
flights between Lagos and London.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. military delegation led by Assistant Secretary of
Defense for International Affairs Franklin Kramer arrived in
Abuja Sunday to discuss bilateral relations with Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The senior military officer said that his visit to Nigeria was
a follow-up of the recent discussions between President Clinton
and his counterpart Gen. Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "we also see an opportunity for extensive dialog
and for consideration of what might be possible in a variety of
areas, including once the transition is completed, in bilateral
military era." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
