<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Reinforce 640,000 Troops If DPRK Attacks S.Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The United States will
reinforce 640,000 troops to South Korea if the country is attacked
by forces of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK),
according to the Defense White Paper 1998 issued by the South
Korean government Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. enforcement, including Army, Navy, Air Force and
Marine forces under the Pacific Command, carrier battle groups and
an amphibious ready group, will join the 690,000 South Korean
troops and the 37,000 U.S. military personnel in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The annual white paper alleged that the DPRK has been further
developing its surprise attack capability on South Korea, posing a
major threat to peace on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang test-fired a rocket to place a satellite in orbit
last month, surprising the world.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the DPRK, with a 100,000-strong special
forces, now has 1.16-million-strong troops, up 13,000 from last
year and it is producing more Shark-class spy submarines, An-2
infiltration aircraft and amphibious hovercraft for infiltration.
</P>
<P>
One of the arguments the white paper presented to back up its
allegation was that Kim Jong-il's assumption of the DPRK's
National Defense Commission early this month means an increase in
military strength.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK is believed to be capable of producing one to two
nuclear bombs, judging from its capability to extract weapons-
grade plutonium but it is not certain whether the country has
actually produced a nuclear bomb. It seems the DPRK has developed
much of the technology needed to produce one, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Seoul came up with the conclusion as Pyongyang threatened in
April this year to stop sealing nuclear fuel rods in its
facilities, a direct violation of its 1994 agreement to drop its
nuclear program, according to the white paper.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the DPRK maintains eight facilities capable of mass
producing chemical agents and several other facilities to produce
biological agents and weapons, and it has developed various
systems to deliver chemical weapons, including Scud-type missiles,
Rodong and Frog missiles, multiple-rocket launchers, field
artillery, fighters and bombers, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
