<HEADLINE> Sino-African Economic And Trade Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Today was the last day of the
first China-Africa Seminar for Economic Management Officials.
</P>
<P>
The two-month seminar on Sino-African economic and trade
cooperation was hosted by the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) and the Foreign Ministry. There were
economic management officials from the governments of 12 African
countries attending.
</P>
<P>
The discussions included China's work in state-owned
enterprises, rural enterprises, coastal economic development
zones, and reforms in the cities of Beijing, Tianjin, and
Shanghai, and provinces of Guangdong, Gansu and Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC Minister Shi Guangsheng and some other Chinese officials
attended the closing ceremony today and MOFTEC Vice-Minister Sun
Guangxiang spoke at the ceremony, saying that China and Africa, in
the new international situation, should strengthen political
cooperation and economic and trade cooperation as well.
</P>
<P>
He said that the seminar is a successful experiment in
furthering Sino-African economic and trade cooperation, and that
China and Africa complement each other economically and that there
are good conditions for furthering economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that in recent years, Sino-African political relations
have grown, and economic and trade cooperation has seen rapid
development and that there are new opportunities with great
potential.
</P>
<P>
Sun said he hopes that officials can help promote Sino-African
economic and trade relations, and that Africa will achieve peace,
development and prosperity through the efforts of the African
people.
</P>
<P>
</P>
