<HEADLINE> Religious Leader: Khomeini's Fatwa Must Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A top Iranian religious
leader reaffirmed that the fatwa or religious decree on the
British writer Salman Rushdie was irrevocable and must be
implemented, local daily Tehran Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to announce that the fatwa is neither
revocable, not alterable and now its implementation is obligatory
on all Muslims throughout the world," the paper quoted a statement
issued by Grand Ayatollah Mohammad Fazel Lankarani on Sunday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Lankarani is one of the seven Marja' Taghlid (Imitation
Source) announced by the Qom Seminary for the Shiite Muslims and
has the authority to issue fatwa.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, Lankarani said that Britain imagined the
fatwa issued by the late Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah Musavi
Khomeini has been withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Islamic seminaries and the revolutionary
people of Iran and the Islamic system would never allow the fatwa
to be overshadowed by day-to-day foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
So far, Lankarani has been the highest Iranian religious figure
who made comments on the recent agreement between Iran and Britain
over the Rushdie issue.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Britain on Thursday agreed to upgrade their diplomatic
relations to ambassadorial level after Tehran assured that the
Iranian government would not take action or assist anyone to
threaten Rushdie's life.
</P>
<P>
Public opinion in Iran noted that the Iranian government
did not make any change in its policy toward Rushdie and his
book the Satanic Verses, which was believed to have insulted the
Islamic Prophet Mohammad.
</P>
<P>
Lankarani blamed the Iranian government for giving the
assurance to London, saying that "if the government of the
Islamic Republic of Iran does not intend to assist the
implementation of this fatwa, it must be among the prime
supporters."
</P>
<P>
He cautioned that Rushdie's book was indeed prepared by the
British government and the author confessed the book was written
under the supervision of the British government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
