<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Bombs Ugandan Village: Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Congolese (K) planes have
bombed Bukaka village of western Bundibgyo District, about five
kilometers inside Uganda, a Ugandan military officer claimed.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's official newspaper The New Vision Monday quoted an
unidentified officer as saying that the war planes made a snap
attack at Bukaka before the Ugandan armed forces responded with
fire. He did not say when.
</P>
<P>
"After dropping the bombs, the planes retreated to Congo (K).
I think such attacks are intended to provoke us into action, but
we have first to study the situation," said the officer.
</P>
<P>
He added that the bombing of the Uganda territory was the
second time in about two months by Congolese war planes. The
first time took place also in Bundibugyo in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi-led rebellion erupted at Goma in eastern Congo on
August 2 and quickly spread to other areas of the country.
Congolese President Laurent Kabila has accused Uganda of backing
the rebels, but Kampala immediately denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni recently admitted the
military presence of Ugandan troops in the vast central African
country for safeguarding the national security of his own
country. He also reaffirmed that Uganda may get involved in the
war only for its own security.
</P>
<P>
The eight-week long conflict in Congo drew regional and global
attention. The Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the
international community are making fresh efforts in a bid to
solve the problem through peaceful means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
