<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 08:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Arab Villagers Launch Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- All Israeli Arab villagers
around the Arab town of Umm Al-Fahem joined a general strike on
Monday to protest against police's crackdown on protesters on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The general strike decision was made Sunday night by the
Israeli Arab Leadership Monitoring Committee following violent
clashes between Israeli police and local Arab residents in which
over 90 people were injured.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's clashes erupted near Umm Al-Fahem, 30 kilometers
southeast of the port city of Haifa, when police moved in in the
morning to tear down a tent erected by Arab protesters who claimed
about 50 hectares of their land were unfairly confiscated by the
Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
The Arab protesters threw rocks and firebombs at the police,
who responded with tear gas and rubber-coated metal bullets. The
clashes lasted till midnight.
</P>
<P>
Most of the injured were brought to hospitals with light or
moderate injuries.
</P>
<P>
Among the injured was Umm Al-Fahem Mayor Sheikh Raad Saleh,
who was hurt in his shoulder and back.
</P>
<P>
At least nine policemen were injured during the clashes by
rocks and Molotov cocktails hurled by protesters.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army said that the disputed area, near the northern
edge of the West Bank, is an army's firing range. The army also
said that an agreement was reached with the residents to
nationalize about 50 hectares of land in exchange for about six
times as much land elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
But Saleh, before he was injured, charged that there was a
hidden agenda behind the expropriation of the land -- to build a
new Jewish city of Irron with 30,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
Saleh's injury fueled the flames and the protesters increased
the rain of stones, bottles and other objects. As many as 800
policemen and border policemen became involved.
</P>
<P>
Close to midnight, the police announced that it was pulling
out of Umm Al-Fahem after an agreement was reached with local
leaders. Under the deal, the land will remain in the hands of
local residents until December, while officials from both sides
try to reach a compromise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
