<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lack of Laws Affects Kenya's Bid to Nab Faulty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Efforts by Kenya's maritime
administrators to nab ships flouting the recently introduced
International Safety Management (ISM) Code are being hampered by
lack of appropriate laws, the East African Weekly said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Shipping sources have expressed fears that Kenya's Indian
Ocean port of Mombasa could still be a safe haven for unseaworthy
vessels as other maritime states clamp down on ships that fail to
comply with the ISM Code.
</P>
<P>
Captain Fred Wahutu, Kenya's Assistant Merchant Shipping
Superintendent, said although Kenya had ratified most of the
conventions required for effective port control by the state, it
had yet to enact appropriate local laws.
</P>
<P>
"We have to be very careful what we detain a ship for... lest
a principal (ship owner) dig deeper into our books," he was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the powers to implement effective port state
control could only come from parliament.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Merchant Shipping Act was reviewed in 1994 by
International Maritime Organization lawyers and local maritime
experts who called for its immediate legislation. But so far the
revised Act has yet to be tabled in parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, industry sources have asked parliament to treat the
matter urgently, saying Kenya stood to lose a lot in the absence
of up-to-date maritime laws, said the weekly.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is among 19 maritime states that signed the Indian Ocean
Memorandum of Understanding on Port State Control, which is aimed
at barring all unseaworthy ships from the region by January 1999.
</P>
<P>
The document also aims to establish cooperation in port state
control, harmonizing inspection and fostering information
exchange.
</P>
<P>
Other signatories were Australia, Bangladesh, Ethiopia,
Eritrea, India, Djibouti, the Maldives, Mauritius, Mozambique,
Myanmar, Oman, Seychelles, South Africa, Sri Lanka, Sudan,
Tanzania and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The International Maritime Organization extended the initial
July 1 deadline for the implementation of the first phase of the
ISM code by two months. The initial phase of the program applies
to passenger ships, tankers, and bulk carriers.
</P>
<P>
Other non-bulk cargo vessels and mobile offshore drilling
units of more than 500 gross weight tonnage (gwt) have to comply
by July 1, 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 08:15 </DATE_TIME>
