<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nairobi, Dar Listed As Big Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Capitals of Kenya and
Tanzania have become major drug trafficking conduits, a report by
the International Criminal Police Organization (Interpol) says.
</P>
<P>
Four Nigerians and one Kenyan were arrested at Nairobi's Jomo
Kenyatta International Airport at the weekend while attempting to
smuggle into Kenya cocaine worth four million Shillings (67,000
U.S. Dollars) by registered mail.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said Monday that the drug initially posted from
Colombia, was intercepted by U.S. customs officials in Miami,
Florida. The U.S. authorities then alerted Kenya after the drug
was re-posted to Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interpol report, nationals of Kenya and
Tanzania are increasingly engaging in trafficking drugs from the
Far East to western Europe. Their main source of heroin is
believed to be Bangkok, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Large consignments of drugs were unknowingly taken to Europe
from Asia via Africa by some of the major European airlines, as
did a number of African airlines, the report said.
</P>
<P>
An analysis of heroin seizures has identified the main African
transit areas as airports at eastern and southern African
capitals.
</P>
<P>
To combat this wave, Interpol had invested 20 million French
Francs in modernizing telecommunications in African national
central bureaux and regional stations.
</P>
<P>
Under the Interpol help, officials from the police,
immigration and customs departments of eastern and southern
African states attended a training seminar on drug law
enforcement in Arusha, northern Tanzania in mid September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 07:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Company Eager to Modernize Turkey's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. defense giant General
Dynamics is trying hard to win over the deal to upgrade Turkey's
M-80 A1 and A3 tanks from the Israeli hands, local newspaper Daily
News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Turkish defense officials as saying that
Turkey and Israel had agreed in principle that the 600 aged
American-made tanks would be modernized by the Israeli Military
Industries and the charge for each tank is 1 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Israeli sources said that it would not take a long time to
finish the modernization.
</P>
<P>
But General Dynamics has asked Israel to give up this deal with
Turkey, Turkish officials said, but without giving further details
of the behind-scene U.S.-Israel bargain. The U.S. company charges
6 million dollars for the modernization of each tank.
</P>
<P>
They said that both Turkish and Israeli sides are aware of this
situation and it is now up to the Israeli government to decide
whether or not to go ahead with the deal.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have cooperated very closely in the defense
industry field during the last few years in an effort to ensure
their own state security in the unstable Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
This relationship has triggered harsh criticism from Iran and
some Arab countries which accuse Ankara of betraying the
interests of the Muslim world by forming a military alliance with
the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Defends Entry of Cathay Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Monday defended his administration's decision of allowing
Hong Kong-based Cathay Pacific Airways to ply domestic routes
following the closure of the national carrier Philippine Airlines
(PAL).
</P>
<P>
He said the entry of Cathay Pacific Airways was merely a
temporary measure to fill in the vacuum left by PAL's closure on
September 23.
</P>
<P>
"I am here just for the interests and welfare of the country.
This is an emergency, so we have to do our best so we will not
disrupt the flow of passengers and business," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
When asked if the government favored Cathay Pacific Airways
over local airlines in coming up with this decision, the president
said his administration will maintain its policy of fair play in
the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific can not continue running PAL's domestic routes
should PAL reopen. In addition, it also can not get more shares in
PAL than that allowed by law, Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific is one of several foreign airlines negotiating
with a government-appointed management committee to take control
of PAL which owed its creditors over two billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We can not violate the law, maybe they can just take the
management," Estrada said, referring to a constitutional provision
limiting foreign shares in Philippine business to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific planes began flying the major domestic routes
Monday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
