<HEADLINE> Chinese Sharpshooters Eye 15 Golds in Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, Southwest China, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Heng,
general coach of Chinese national shooting team, said here on
Monday that he belived Chinese sharpshooters can bring home at
least 15 gold medals in the Asian Games to be held at Bangkok, Th
ailand in December.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident to win more than half of the 34 gold medals
on offer. Exactly, at least 15," said Zhang, who is here
attending the inaugural China shooting masters grand prix.
</P>
<P>
China captured the world team title after collecting 12 gold
medals in the World Shooting Championships in Barcelona, Spain,
last July, the first time the team's world top honor was won by
an Asian country.
</P>
<P>
"China enjoys a comfortable upper hand over all the other
Asian opponents in shooting," Zhang said. "But our goal is not to
win gold medals in Asian Games. It is just a warm-up for the 2000
Olympic Games."
</P>
<P>
In the 1984 Olympic Games at Los Angles, sharpshooter Xu
Haifeng made history by winning China's first Olympic gold
medal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
