<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Georges Strikes U.S. Southern Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Hurricane Georges struck
the coast areas of the Gulf of Mexico Sunday, bringing high wind
and heavy rain that drove thousands of people in southern Alabama,
Mississippi and Luisiana into shelters, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The hurricane stirred up seven-meter-high waves that clipped
off fishing piers along Alabama's coast, smashing over concrete
walls to demolish a fishing pier.
</P>
<P>
In the coast areas of Alabama, several roads were closed
because of flooding, downed trees and toppled utility poles.
Thousands were without power and shelters filled up as the storm
intensified.
</P>
<P>
In Mississippi, widespread power outages were reported as the
storm advanced with wind gusts up to 88 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
In Louisiana, high winds knocked out power to at least 38,000
customers in the southeastern part of the state. Tens of thousands
flocked to the city's nine shelters.
</P>
<P>
Thousands fled New Orleans and more than 1.5 million people
were ordered or urged to vacate the city and coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
All flights in and out were canceled. A curfew was in place for
New Orleans and surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
Along the Gulf Coast in Mississippi, Alabama and Florida, many
schools were closed at least through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
By 11 p.m. EDT, the hurricane's center was about 110 kilometers
south-southeast of Biloxi, Mississippi, and about 170 kilometers
east-southeast of New Orleans. Wind blew at about 170 kph, and
forecasters said that might increase to 190 kph.
</P>
<P>
Georges was moving north-northwest. The National Hurricane
Center said that the hurricane's center was expected to reach the
Gulf Coast on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Georges was viewed as the most serious storm to threaten New
Orleans since 1969, when Camille slammed into the coast of
Mississippi and Louisiana, causing flooding as far north as
Virginia and West Virginia and killing 259 people.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 deaths had been blamed on the hurricane in the
Caribbean. No lives have been reported lost in the United States
since the storm struck the nation's southern coast on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
