<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Seek Emergency Aid From WB, IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
negotiate with the World Bank (WB) and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) for emergency assistance, particularly for balance of
payment support to meet import needs, The Financial Express daily
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Finance Minister S.A.M.S Kabria while
talking to an independent news agency in Dhaka Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The minister is scheduled to leave here for Ottawa, Canada, on
Sunday to attend the Commonwealth finance ministers conference,
and then he will go to Washington to participate in the annual
conference of the WB and IMF to be held there early next month.
</P>
<P>
He would seek a total of 335 million U.S. dollars -- 200
million from the WB and 135 million from the IMF -- as emergency
assistance.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations will be held during the two financial
agencies' conference.
</P>
<P>
"There are matters to be negotiated, and they might ask us to
meet certain conditions, to meet certain reforms which are usually
tough to meet," Kabria predicted.
</P>
<P>
He added that during his address to the conference he would
appeal for assistance to rebuild the flood-ravaged Bangladesh.
"I'll tell them about the trail of devastation left by the longest
ever flooding."
</P>
<P>
"It is very important to us that donors are responding with
additional funds to repair the infrastructure," he said. "All the
donors whom I met told me that they will provide assistance to
repair and reconstruct the damaged infrastructure."
</P>
<P>
This is the main reason for the country's appeal for emergency
assistance from the WB and the IMF, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Huge food import, necessitated by a staggering crop loss of at
least two million tons of grain due to flooding, would put a heavy
burden on the country's foreign exchange reserve if the import
bills are not met by additional foreign exchange funds.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided to import one million tons of
foodgrains, of which tender for only one-third has been floated.
</P>
<P>
The worst-ever flooding in a century in Bangladesh had gripped
as much as two-thirds of the country for ten weeks and affected
about half its 127 million people, with nearly 30 million of them
hit seriously, leaving over 1,000 dead and inflicting a
preliminary estimated loss of about 3.4 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
