<HEADLINE> Arena's Coach Status Is Uncertain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- D.C. United president
Kevin Payne has informed U.S. Soccer Federation officials that he
will not release coach Bruce Arena from his contract to be the
head coach of the U.S. national soccer team here today.
</P>
<P>
Payne said if Arena were allowed to coach both teams for a
short period, it would be possible.
</P>
<P>
Arena, the leading candidate to become the U.S. national team
coach, in in the third year of a four-year deal with the D.C.
United team, which closed its regular season today.
</P>
<P>
USSF officials had planned to name a new coach before the
U.S.team's next game on November 6 against Australia in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
United's Major League Soccer season cuold last until October
25, when the league's championship game is scheduled to be
played. But United also is finalizing plans to play Brazilian
power Vasco da Gama in the Interamerican Cup in consecutive
weekends in November, and Payne said he wants Arena to guide the
club in those games.
</P>
<P>
"We consider the Inteamerican Cup to be extremely important
for us, the league and for soccer in the United States," Payne
said of the event, which matches the North American club champion
against the South American titlist. "We want Bruce coaching us in
that."
</P>
<P>
Concerning a possible offer from the USSF, Arena said:"I'm not
worried about it now." Arena said. Asked if he had been in
contact with any USSF officials in the past week, Arena did not
respond.
</P>
<P>
USSF President Bob Contiguglia did not return phone messages
Two USSF sources said Arena - the only American among the four
finalists - remains the front-runner, but Contiguglia still wants
to talk to Carlos Queiroz, a former Portugal national team coach
who has worked as a USSF consultant.
</P>
<P>
Both sources also said Bora Milutinovic, the U.S. World Cup
coach in 1994 who took over the MLS's New York/New Jersey
MetroStars last week, and former Brazil coach Carlos Alberto
Parreira have fallen behind the other two candidates.
</P>
<P>
As the national coaching saga continues, Arena is concerned
about getting United ready for its playoff opener Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
