<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preliminary Official Results Confirm Schroeder's Triumph </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The preliminary official vote
statistics have confirmed a landmark victory for Germany's Social
Democratic Party (SPD) and its chancellor candidate Gerhard
Schroeder in the country's general elections on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the preliminary official results released early
Monday morning, the SPD scored 40.9 percent of the vote against
35.2 percent for Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Union
(CDU)/Christian Social Union (CSU) conservative alliance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ecologist Greens, the potential junior partner
in a SPD-led ruling coalition, scored 6.7 percent against 6.2
percent won by the Free Democratic Party (FDP), the junior partner
in Kohl's current ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
The Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS), which grew out of the
former East Germany's communist party, also broke the 5-percent
mark for the first time since the German reunification in 1990 by
winning 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The SPD is eligible for 298 seats in the Bundestag (lower house
of parliament) compared with 245 seats for Kohl's conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The Greens would get 47 seats, the FDP 44 and the PDS 35.
</P>
<P>
It means that if the SPD and the Greens could negotiate a
so-called "Red-Green" coalition, they would have a relatively
comfortable majority of 21 seats in parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
