<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Oil Refinery Project in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Construction work on a 1,600
million U.S. dollar oil refinery project at Hambantota in the
South of Sri Lanka will commence next February, according to the
Board of Investment (BOI) Monday.
</P>
<P>
The project is being promoted by a consortium of six European
and Asian investors of which the regional Cooperative Petroleum
Refinery International of Hong Kong is the chief promoter, the BOI
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement of the project, the foreign investors must
invest 600 million dollars within the first year and the balance
of 1,000 million dollars in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The project is to span 1,000 acres of land and generate 2,000
jobs. It will also aim at exporting 200,000 barrels of refined
oil per month and generate 300 megawatts of power.
</P>
<P>
While preliminary surveys for the project have been completed
the final designs and engineering surveys will be attempted by the
consortia of investors.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that there will be a large component of local
contractors in the project in terms of road building and the
construction of other related infrastructure facilities, according
to the sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
