<HEADLINE> Myanmar NGO Gets Award for Primary Health Care Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar Maternal and Child
Welfare Association, a non-governmental organization (NGO),
received an award here Sunday from the World Health Organization
(WHO) for its primary health care development.
</P>
<P>
The award, presented by the Southeast Asia Region Organization
of the WHO in commemoration of its 50th anniversary, is for the
NGO's outstanding performance in catering to the primary Health
Care of mothers and children as well as the public.
</P>
<P>
The NGO generally undertakes tasks of uplifting of public
health standard, disease control and treatment, health-related
educational and social services, and improvement of livelihood of
mothers.
</P>
<P>
The organization's Health Care projects cover 313 townships out
of 326 in the country with participation of 550,000 members.
</P>
<P>
It caters to the Health Care of over 200,000 expectant mothers
at its midwifery clinics every year and nourishes for about
800,000 children.
</P>
<P>
The organization is also running 195 pre-primary schools which
look after 8,000 children, providing stipends for 50,000 children
as a contribution towards "Education for All by the Year 2000" and
opening literacy courses in 71 townships for 15,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The NGO was formed in 1991. 
</P>
