<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economy Expected to Recover Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Good progress in structural
and financial reforms in Thailand will help lead to economic
recovery by mid-1999, Merrill Phatra Securities said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai-U.S. joint venture said in a statement available here
Monday that Thailand is close to a return to international capital
markets as indicated by economic factors.
</P>
<P>
While Thailand's financial markets held a minute share of
global market capital -- about 0.11 percent, opportunities had
opened as the economy was expected to recover.
</P>
<P>
Mexico took about 18 months to recover from its currency and
economic crash in late 1994. Similar parallels between Thailand
and Mexico could be drawn, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said the first step on the road to recovery was to correct
imbalances in exchange rates, trade and current accounts.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several months, the baht has stabilized at 41-42
to the U.S. dollar. On Friday it jumped to 38-39, aided by
portfolio investment flows and a weaker dollar in anticipation of
U.S. interest rate cuts this week.
</P>
<P>
Short-term interest rates have also fallen sharply in recent
months, causing growth in bank deposits to slow down and
investment flows to increase, in anticipation of higher returns.
</P>
<P>
Continued moderate inflation would help strengthen confidence,
leading to economic growth and a pickup in real wages and
employment.
</P>
<P>
Increased equity in investments, particularly from abroad,
means that equity would begin to replace past reliance on bank
loans as the foundation for the country's investment base.
</P>
<P>
Foreign debt stands at just under 90 billion U.S. dollars, with
up to 40 percent short-term. While most companies have been able
to restructure and roll over loans, the heavy dependence on debt
for operating and investment capital has placed many companies in
a squeeze for cash.
</P>
<P>
Among the most attractive investment choices for foreign
investors are state enterprises, particularly in energy, transport
and telecommunications, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
