<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Export 380,000 Tons of Coffee Bean in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam will export 380,000
tons of coffee bean in the 1997-98 fiscal year ending October,
which is expected to earn more than 500 million U.S. dollars,
according to latest official reports.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam now ranks second in Asia in terms of coffee production
and first in Asia for coffee export volume. Most of its coffee is
of the robusta variety.
</P>
<P>
More than 82 percent of Vietnam's coffee was bought by the
United States, Germany, Spain, Britain, Italy, Poland, France,
Austria, the Republic of Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Prolonged drought this year is estimated to cause losses of
between 80,000-100,000 tons of coffee bean to the coming 1998-99
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
However, coffee growers still cherish a hope to harvest between
380,000 to 400,000 tons of bean and attain an export earning of
560 million dollars next year, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the country has about 300,000 hectares of coffee
land and plans to expand the acreage to 350,000 hectares by the
year 2005, aiming to bring national coffee output to
420,000-450,000 tons a year.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are also being made to cultivate the arabica variety of
coffee, which has a higher economic value, and to improve coffee
processing technology, the reports added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
