<HEADLINE> Other Sports Leaders Worry About NBA Labor Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Union leaders in other
sports said it doesn't look like the NBA's current stalemate will
have a happier ending.
</P>
<P>
"Management is taking a very hard-line stance in a belief that
the players will buckle," said Don FEhr, executive director of
the U.S. Major League Baseball Players Association. "If they
don't, then the league is in the soup."
</P>
<P>
The NBA lockout is approaching its third month.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. national hockey league owners in 1994 locked out
players, resulting in the cancellation of 34 games at the start
of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
The national football league's 1987 player strike forced the
cancellation of one week's games, and three other week's games
were played with replacement players.
</P>
<P>
Bob Goodenow, head of the NHL Players' Association, blames NBA
Commissioner David Stern for the league's labor predicament.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think David has a respect for his players and his
product," said Goodenow, who negotiated his labor agreement with
NHL Commissioner Gary Bettman, a former NBA official. "His
inability to put a program together without resorting to this
attack on the players - which is what this is - makes me wonder
what his true intentions are." 
</P>
