<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price System Plays Active Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- China's current price system
is playing a bigger role in the country's two-decade-old
market-driven economy than that during the era of command economy.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily" reported today that in China now, prices of about
93 percent of products at the retail level are set by the
market. Those decided by authorities account for only six percent
and the prices allowed to move inside a government-set range
account for the remaining one percent.
</P>
<P>
"The price system reform has played an active part in fueling
the country's economic growth," the newspaper quoted a report from
the State Statistics Bureau as saying.
</P>
<P>
The price reform, initiated in 1979, also brought a new
challenge for the government -- the taming of of inflation, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
Without the government's direct restrictive measures, the
growth rate of prices would have soared to unfavorable heights at
a time when the economy overheated.
</P>
<P>
In the past two decades, China dealt with two rounds of serious
price inflation, peaking in 1988 and 1994 respectively. Retail
prices surged 18.5 percent in 1988 and 21.7 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Tightened fiscal and monetary policies, along with strict
control on expansion of investment and consumption, enabled the
government to suppress the two rounds of inflation.
</P>
<P>
In the process, the government also accumulated useful
experiences regarding how to exert macroeconomic control in a
market economy, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Excessive austerity measures imposed during the 1986-90 economic
cycle curbed inflation, but it also resulted in a sluggish
economic performance. The growth rate of the gross domestic
product (GDP) dropped from 13.5 in 1985 to 4.1 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
More mild and sophisticated measures taken by the government to
deal with the second round of inflation resulted in a "soft
landing" last year, with inflation effectively curtailed while
economic growth rate not dampened.
</P>
<P>
China's GDP grew by 8.8 percent last year, while retail prices
growth rate stood at a slight 0.8 percent, said the State
Statistics Bureau.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Update Fish Product Processing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- China will further update its
fish processing technology and equipment and learn from foreign
advanced expertise to meet a growing market demand, today's "China
Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed at the Fish Utilization Symposium of the
Asia-Pacific Region, which ended on Saturday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Experts in the region reviewed technical and policy measures
regarding efficient use of aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
China's fisheries sector has expanded on a steady and fast
track, with a production ranking first in the world for eight
years, said Chen Delong, an official with the Fisheries Bureau
under the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of the year, China's output in
the sector totalled 16.73 million tons, an increase of 11 percent
from the same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
However, only 27.8 percent of annual aquatic products are
processed to add value. This is less than in developed countries,
noted Chen.
</P>
<P>
China's fledging aquatic processing industry has played an
increasingly important role in ensuring food supply and improving
people's diet, said Chen.
</P>
<P>
In China, aquatic products averaged 29 kilograms per person in
1997, above the world's average.
</P>
<P>
The country has more than 5,860 enterprises engaged in
refrigerating and processing aquatic products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
