<P>
He hoped that at the beginning of 1999 when Germany starts the
rotating presidency of the European Union (EU), the organization's
agenda for the year 2000 would be ready. This is important for
Finland which would serve as the EU's rotating presidency at the
latter half of the year, Lipponen said.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish prime minister also thanked his German counterpart
Helmut Kohl for his contributions to the EU's member countries,
saying that under Kohl's influence, Finland became a member of the
organization and found it's place in the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
