<HEADLINE> Telephone Harassment Listed in Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Dali County People's
Court in north China's Shaanxi Province has accepted the legal
indictment of a woman suing her former boss for sex harassment
over telephone. This is the first lawsuit over telephone harassing
in China.
</P>
<P>
Ji Meili, a 43-year-old business woman, took legal proceedings
against He Kaiyou, director of Dali County Agricultural Bureau,
for allegedly harassing her for 20 days in August, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Ji claimed that she would be waken up by telephons almost every
midnight and a man would harass her with the language such as "I
want to make love with you" and "How about your body?" The
telephone calls came again and again and would last about two
hours every night.
</P>
<P>
According to Ji, the harassment not only disturbed her, but
also wrecked her family. Her husband misunderstood her and they
lived apart.
</P>
<P>
Ji asked the local telecommunication bureau to trace the calls
and was told that they came from mobile phone and a family phone
alleged to belong to He Kaiyou.
</P>
<P>
She said He was her former boss and there has been conflicts
between them at work.
</P>
<P>
In her plaint, Ji has asked for four rulings against He
including a compensation for direct loss valued at 7,880 yuan
(about (US$949), another payment of 10,000 yuan for emotional
distress and and open apology.
</P>
<P>
The court said it will hold hearings early next month, said the
newspaper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
