<HEADLINE> Release of Clinton Testimony Tape May Have Backfired: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The decision of the U.S.
House of Representatives to release the videotape of President
Bill Clinton's grand jury testimony may have hurt Congress rather
than the president, a poll released on Sunday showed.
</P>
<P>
The poll commissioned by Time magazine and CNN television found
that the Republican-led Congress' approval rating dropped to 54
percent from 63 percent since the tape ran on national television
last Monday, while the Democratic president's approval rating
remained at more than 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 1,019 adults was conducted in the three days
after the airing of the four-hour tape on Monday. The survey had a
margin of error of 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of the respondents said they believed Republicans
were acting "too partisan" in their investigation of the
president. They were split on whether they thought the president's
fellow Democrats in Congress were acting fairly.
</P>
<P>
In the new poll, 61 percent approved of Clinton's job
performance, compared to 63 percent in a September 16-17 survey.
In each poll, one-third disapproved.
</P>
<P>
By a 53-41 margin, respondents in the latest poll said they
wanted their members of Congress to vote against beginning a formal
impeachment investigation against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The House Judiciary Committee is to make a recommendation next
week to the full House on whether to start such a proceeding.
</P>
<P>
The poll found that most Americans believe Clinton should
remain in office, though many contend he deserves some form of
punishment.
</P>
<P>
Just 12 percent said they favored impeachment, while 23 percent
said they thought he should resign. Twenty-nine percent favor
censure while 34 percent said no action should be taken against
him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
