<HEADLINE> Sweden Edges Spain 4-1 to Reach Davis Cup Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 27 (Xinhua) -- defending champion Sweden
overwhelmed Spain 4-1 in its Davis Cup world group semi-final tie
after splitting the reverse singles matches on Sunday and
advanced to the final against Italy in December.
</P>
<P>
Jonas Bjorkman, who took three points for the second
consecutive tie, rolled over Carlos Moya 6-2, 7-5 in the first
match on Sunday before Julian Alonso, a late replacement for
Spanish number two Alex Corretja, salvaged some pride for his
country by defeating Thomas Johansson 6-1, 7-6 (7-3).
</P>
<P>
The Spaniards, favoured on the strength of Moya's fifth place
and Corretja's seventh in the world rankings, managed to take
only one set in the weekend's first three matches as Sweden took
a 3-0 lead, reducing Sunday's dead reverse singles to
best-of-three-set contests.
</P>
<P>
Bjorkman, ranked 13th in the world, said: "I enjoyed playing
today. My play is fine at the moment so I am satisfied and
looking forward to the final."
</P>
<P>
Sweden will take on Italy looking for its seventh Davis Cup
triumph. Italy beat the United States 4-1 in the another
semi-final on Sunday. 
</P>
