<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines May Re-Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- After four days of being
closed, the national flag carrier Philippine Airlines (PAL) may
re-open after its ground crew union accepted the management's
offer.
</P>
<P>
During last-ditch talks with labor officials at President
Joseph Estrada's residence in Manila, the union finally agreed to
suspend its collective bargaining agreement for 10 years as
demanded by the management, Business World reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In exchange, the management will give 20 percent of the
airlines ownership and three seats in the board of directors to
the employees, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that President Estrada has announced that the crisis
caused by the sudden closure of PAL Wednesday is over. However, it
was yet unclear if the management will accept the union's
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a PAL official said that even if the two sides reach
an agreement, the airlines should also be downsized and may run
domestic routes only.
</P>
<P>
PAL had suffered a heavy loss of 2.1 billion U.S. dollars as of
June this year. The strike staged by the labor union exacerbated
the crisis and finally forced the 57-year-old airlines to close
shop.
</P>
<P>
Starting Monday, Hong Kong-based Cathay Pacific begins flying
the major domestic routes abandoned by Philippine Airlines.
</P>
</TEXT>
