<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Learning About China In Poor Mountain Villages (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- An international youth
expedition organized by the British charity group Raleigh
International has spent the past three months camping and working
in outlying mountain villages in east China's Shandong and Jiangsu
provinces.
</P>
<P>
The 90 young people from 10 different countries have braved the
summer heat to help farmers build small dams and village
schools. They have cooked meals and washed clothes by themselves
and slept in tents they carried in.
</P>
<P>
One British member of the team said that if he had only visited
Beijing, Shanghai, and Hong Kong, he would never have seen what
the real China is.
</P>
<P>
At Haotan, a village of 200 people at the foot of Taishan, the
highest mountain in Shandong, the team helped villagers, whose
average income is less than 2,000 yuan (240 U.S. dollars) a year,
build several small dams for water and soil conservation.
</P>
<P>
Li Yuantai, a 73-year-old villager, said, "These foreign kids
are quite good. They work hard and can stand the harsh living
conditions, and even some of our villagers are no match to them."
But, he said with a smile, "these kids have no idea about
frugality. They used more than 50 bags of cement on the dam,
something that would normally need a dozen bags at most."
</P>
<P>
The only foreigners Li had seen before were Japanese troops who
intruded into China in the late 1930s and early 1940s. Li was only
18 then and was forced to build watchtowers for the Japanese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Learning About China From Poor Mountain Villages (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Raleigh recruits more than 100 people aged from 17 to 25 years
worldwide every year to go to developing countries to do various
challenging community and environmental projects and to give them
experience and an understanding of their potential.
</P>
<P>
The team also helped build a room for a watchman and a canteen
at a new elementary school in Xiagang, another village several
miles from Haotan and became English teachers for the
approximately 100 pupils in the school, who had never heard the
language before.
</P>
<P>
One fourth-grade girl said that their class was very funny and
interesting that the pupils loved it, and a team member from Chile
said that villagers were "very curious" toward them and often
visited their campsite. Sometimes the villagers tried hard to
communicate with the team members through sign language or by
drawing pictures, but more often just sat there quietly watching
the team working.
</P>
<P>
And they were often invited to the villagers' homes to eat and
whenever they walked through the village, their pockets would be
filled with dates, nuts and other small gifts.
</P>
<P>
The village folks, when compared with those in the West, one
member who was suntanned after weeks of work outdoors said, were
not affluent by the Western standards, but incredibly generous and
welcoming. They're are also happy, contented and hard-working, and
materialistic things are not so important to them, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Learning About China From Poor Mountain Villages (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This year was Raleigh's first expedition to China. Most of the
team members had never come to visit China and had little idea
about what it was like.
</P>
<P>
But, a Japanese member, Kumi Tanaka, said, "China is such a
nice and beautiful country, and there are so many people and so
many life styles here," and a British team member, Andy Bell,
pitched in by acknowledging that he saw a very wide diversity
between life in China's modern cities and its remote villages, but
that he felt "very privileged to be able to come to such remote
places in China which most Westerners have never been to." One
could probably acquaint himself more with the Chinese culture in
the country's rural areas than urbanites who are confined only to
cities and towns can, he noted.
</P>
<P>
A China Youth Development Foundation official says that this
year's Raleigh Expedition was unprecedented. "In the past, young
foreign visitors only had an opportunity to see major cities," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Raymond K.F. Ch'ien, chairman of Hong Kong's Inchcape Pacific
Ltd., sponsor of the expedition, said that before China adopted
its policy of opening to the outside world, such an expedition
would have been "unthinkable", and the fact that this large
international cross-cultural group of young people was allowed to
spend three months living and working in China's interior areas
epitomizes the remarkable progress that has been scored and
China's commitment to the reform and opening-up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
