<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Machinery Producers Face Foreign Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese machinery
manufacturers are facing intense competition from abroad in
winning orders of new infrastructural and industrial projects,
"China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Spurred by the huge investment pledged by the central
government, demand for machinery and equipment used in railway
expansion, water harnessing projects and petrochemical plants will
soon surge.
</P>
<P>
As much as 250 million yuan (30 million U.S. dollars) will be
pumped into the railway sector alone from now through 2003. The
project to build a 1,300-km-long high-speed railway from Beijing
to Shanghai will begin in 2000.
</P>
<P>
But analysts say if domestic manufacturers don't step up
efforts to upgrade products, stress quality and enhance services,
they will lose a huge market share to their foreign counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Qi Zihong, director of equipment supply department of the China
Railway Engineering Corp, said, "The quality of domestically made
engineering machinery has improved significantly during the past
few years, but still lags far behind those imported from advanced
nations."
</P>
<P>
Poor reliability, few varieties, short life-span, lack of
after-sales services and customer training have become the principal
drawbacks for the domestic machinery and equipment suppliers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
When there is a problem with imported equipment, following
identification of responsibilities, the foreign maker will usually
send the related components to the work spot soon so that the
equipment can start operation again, Qi said.
</P>
<P>
If the same case happened to locally made product, its
manufacturers would pass the buck to each other and cause losses
to the customer, which would thereby certainly bring about an
adverse effect to its future sales, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Schroeder Declares End of Kohl Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Gerhard Schroeder on Sunday
brought Germany's Social Democratic Party (SPD) back to power in
Bonn after 16 years in opposition in the German political arena
dominated by veteran chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
According to German television projections released late Sunday
evening, the center-left SPD scored over 41 percent of the vote in
the general elections, some five points ahead of Kohl's Christian
Democratic Union (CDU)/Christian Social Union (CSU) conservative
alliance.
</P>
<P>
"After 16 years, the era of Kohl has ended today... The voters
have chosen in this election a change of generations," Schroeder
told a cheering crowd of supporters at the SPD headquarters in
Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, already Germany's longest-serving chancellor and the most
durable Western leader in the post-war era, swiftly conceded
defeat -- the worst one for his party since 1949.
</P>
<P>
"The election result is clear, the Social Democrats won. The
voters have clearly opted for Red-Green," Kohl said, referring to
the SPD and its potential junior coalition partners, the Greens.
</P>
<P>
He also declared his intention to step down as the chairman of
the CDU, a post he held since 1973.
</P>
<P>
"I will discuss with the CDU board tomorrow and ask them not to
nominate me again for the chair of the party at the next party
congress," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a reference to his past, Kohl said, "I'm thankful to all
those who helped us in the last 16 years, also to those many
abroad who helped pave our way as friends and partners. Many of
our triumphs were made possible by our partners and friends. It
was a great time. We achieved a lot but as democrats, we accept
the decision of the voters.... Life goes on."
</P>
<P>
Despite his defeat, Kohl has secured a place in history as the
architect of Germany's reunification in 1990 and a leading
champion for European unity.
</P>
<P>
But with unemployment hovering at a near post-war record high
of over 4 million and widespread disillusionment among eastern
Germans with his broken promises of "flourish landscapes" after
reunification, Kohl has to face a growing desire for a change in
German politics.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, campaigning on a concept which he called the "New
Center," has won strong support from the middle-of-the-road voters
by pledging to combine modernity and reforms with more social
justice.
</P>
<P>
"Our concept has been to aim for the New Center. It's apparent
that this concept was the right way," Schroeder said on Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
He also vowed continuity in foreign policy and pledged to
strive for economic stability and more security in social order.
</P>
<P>
But first of all, he said, "My most important goal is the fight
against the plague of mass unemployment."
</P>
<P>
It was still not clear whether the SPD would be able to
negotiate a deal with the ecologist Greens to form a coalition.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder did not rule out any coalition possibilities. As the
strongest party in parliament, the SPD could now choose to rule
with the Greens, or the CDU, or even with the current junior
partner in Kohl's government, the Free Democratic Party (FDP).
</P>
<P>
Latest election projections put the Greens at 6.7 percent and
the FDP at 6.2 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said he would wait for the final results and would
decide in the next few days on which party the SPD would negotiate
for a ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
"I want a government with a stable majority," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Kohl and leader of his Bavarian sister party CSU, Theo
Waigel, have spoken against an alliance with the SPD. FDP leader
Wolfgang Gerhardt also made it clear that his party would go into
the opposition.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary projections, the Party of Democratic
Socialism (PDS), which grew out of the former East German
communist party, also achieved a big victory on Sunday by winning
over 5 percent of the vote, its best since the 1990 reunification.
</P>
<P>
But Schroeder had said earlier that he did not want to rely on
the support of the PDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: "China Will Become World's Largest Advertising Market" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- "In New York, I shocked the
U.S. investment community by telling them that China will become
the world's biggest advertising market in the next decade," noted
Kevin Roberts in his address to the first China International
Brand Strategy Conference in Beijing this year.
</P>
<P>
As the CEO of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, one of the top 10 advertising
agencies in the world, Kevin didn't exaggerate.
</P>
<P>
China's advertising industry has registered robust and rapid
development since 1979 when the country's first commercial was
broadcast on the Shanghai TV Station.
</P>
<P>
The business volume of the country's advertising industry
increased from 2.5 billion yuan in 1990 to 46.2 billion yuan in
1997, with the number of advertising agencies growing from 1,076
to 29,010 and professionals from 26,440 to 319,092 during the
period, according to figures from the State Administration for
Industry and Commerce, which is in charge of the nation's
advertising sector.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also indicate that the growth rate of China's
advertising sector has been, on the average, four to six times
higher than that of the GDP since 1978 when the country began
implementing its policy of reforming and opening up.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted in Beijing, Shanghai and Nanjing
revealed that some 92.5 percent of the respondents were able to
tell one or two advertising slogans in two seconds.
</P>
<P>
This means that ads are playing an ever more important role in
China's daily life.
</P>
<P>
Just as one insider said, in today's China, it is getting hard
for consumers to accept goods which have not been advertised.
People even decide what movie to see by looking through
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, this enormous market has also attracted world-famous
advertising agencies, following their clients. The world top 10
advertising giants, such as Ogilvy &AMP; Mather, Dentsu, Leo Burnett
and Grey have already established joint ventures in China.
</P>
<P>
"For multinational ad agencies, this is a market you have to
enter, you have no choice. If your clients have entered this
market, but you don't, how can you provide a global service for
them?" said Viveca Chan, Chairman and CEO of the Grey China
Advertising Co. Ltd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastman Opens JV in Nanjing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A new large Sino-US
petrochemicals manufacturing joint venture was officially signed
in Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province on Friday,
today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, Yangzi Petrochemical Industrial Corp
(YPIC) and Eastman Chemical Ltd inked a contract to form the
30-million-U.S. dollar joint venture to produce Eastotac
hydrocarbon tackifying resin for adhesive manufactures.
</P>
<P>
Eastman Chemical Ltd is a subsidiary of US-based Eastman
Chemical Co while YPIC is an affiliate of Yangzi Petrochemical
Corp.
</P>
<P>
Construction is expected to begin in mid-1999 and be completed
by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Eastman's Eastotac resin is used by adhesive manufacturers to
produce hot-melt adhesives for infant and feminine hygiene
products, packaging, glue sticks, tapes, labels, and other
adhesive applications.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing Yangzi Eastman Chemical will be a 50-50 joint
venture. The plant will use C5 distillate, a by-product from the
manufacture of ethylene, to produce high quality hydrocarbon
tackifying resin.
</P>
<P>
The new plant will be Eastman's first one in China. Currently,
all Eastotac resin is manufactured by Eastman in the United
States, the paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
