<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0840 GMT, September 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Violent clashes broke out between Israeli Arabs
and Israeli police Sunday over a land dispute in north-central
Israel, injuring 38, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The clashes took place near the Arab town of Umm Al-Fahem, 30
kilometers southeast of the port city of Haifa, when police moved
in to tear down a tent erected by Arab protesters three weeks
ago. The protesters claimed the land was unfairly confiscated by
the Israeli army. Israeli authorities have said that the disputed
area is within an Israeli army firing range. (Israel-Clash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Gerhard Schroeder, chancellor candidate of Germany's
main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD), won the general
election Sunday, bringing to the incumbent German chancellor
Helmut Kohl a clear defeat.
</P>
<P>
According to the projections released by the ARD network,
Schroeder's SPD has won 41.2 percent of the vote against 35.7
percent for Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and its
Bavarian sister party, Christian Social Union (CSU).
(Germany-Schroeder-Win)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- An senior Iranian official announced on Sunday that
Iran would issue green cards for refugees living in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Farhad Barikani, an official from the Interior Ministry in
charge of the refugees camps said that all foreign subjects such
as Afghan and Iraqi refugees would soon have their green cards.
He said that some 2 million foreign citizens are living in Iran,
of which nearly 1.4 million are Afghans. (Iran-Refugees-Cards)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Three veteran politicians mentioned as possible
mediators between U.S. President Bill Clinton and the
Republican-controlled Congress over the Lewinsky affair say there
won't be a deal before the November elections.
</P>
<P>
"Probably not much can happen until maybe next year," said
former Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
"Right now, instead of a race to judgment, you are looking at a
race to the election," said former White House Chief of Staff Leon
Panetta, who appeared Sunday with Dole and former Senate
Republican leader Howard Baker on NBC's "Meet the Press."
(US- Lewinsky-Deal Unlikely) 
</P>
</TEXT>
