<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Leagues' Proposal Isn't New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A NBA Players Association
official claimed today the league's latest contract proposal to
the players contains "nothing new on the core issues" of the
labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
The official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said
the union was in the process of responding to the league.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing new on the core issues we've been fighting
over and some of which we want to talk about later in the week,"
the union official said. "We want to give our response first to
the NBA and then to the press."
</P>
<P>
The owners this spring exercised an option to re-open their
collective bargaining agreement with the players, which had three
years remaining.
</P>
<P>
There has been little progress in talks. The league is seeking
to institute an inflexible ceiling on team payrolls and eliminate
the so-called Larry Bird exception to the league's salary cap.
</P>
<P>
The Bird exception allows teams to re-sign their own players
without regard to the cap.
</P>
<P>
The league locked out the players on July 1, and there has
been only one formal bargaining session since. Last week, the
league undefinitely postponed the start of training camps, which
had been set for October 5, and cancelled 24 preseason games that
had been scheduled to be played from October 13 to 16.
</P>
<P>
That would mean a deal would have to be reached before the
October 18 deadline by which grievance arbitrator John Feerick
has to rule on the union's contention that the teams must pay
players who have guaranteed contracts even though there is a
lockout.
</P>
<P>
Legal observers which no allegiance to eigher side say
Feerick's ruling will be pivotal to the dispute because a ruling
in the union's favor will put financial pressure on the teams.
</P>
<P>
NBA commissioner David Stern said he wants to eliminate the
open-ended aspect of the Bird exception, which has been a
foundation of NBA labor agreements for the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
But he also said teams should have "an edge" in the bidding
for their own players, and he suggested that teams give their own
players long-term contracts and higher rises than they do to free
agents they sign from other teams.
</P>
<P>
No such language was included in Friday's new offer, the union
official said.
</P>
<P>
League spokesman Chris Brienza said "We decided we do not want
to comment publicly on what the contents of our proposals are."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980928.0252 </DOCNO>
