<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henman Secures Davis Cup Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Tim Henman put Britain back
into the Davis Cup World Group for the first time since 1992 with
a 7-6, 6-2, 7-6 victory over India's Leander Paes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The play was delayed for 43 minutes after heavy rain swamped t
he court but once play started Henman, with Britain leading 2-1
after the first two days, began confidently.
</P>
<P>
The British number one broke for 3-1 but then immediately lost
his service before breaking again for 4-2.
</P>
<P>
Paes, who was always prepared to chip and charge when Henman
missed his first serve, broke back again in the ninth game with
the first set moving to a tie-break.
</P>
<P>
Henman, keeping his cool, went to 6-3 as Paes missed two vital
volleys to give Henman the upper hand after 49 minutes play.
</P>
<P>
The Briton then raced through the second set in 29 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Paes won the opening game but then appeared to run out of
steam, losing five successive games for Henman to lead 5-1.
</P>
<P>
The Indian held his serve in the seventh game but Henman held
his own delivery in the following game to move 2-0 up.
</P>
<P>
Paes appeared to gain a new lease of life in the third set but
Henman finally scrambled home in a 7-5 tie breaker to win 7-6
(7-3), 6-2, 7-6 (7-5) after two hours and three minutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
